# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fluid-dynamics-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle can be derived from the principle of conservation of energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] This states that, in a steady flow, the sum of all forms of energy in a fluid is the same at all points that are free of viscous forces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] This requires that the sum of kinetic energy, potential energy and internal energy remains constant.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Thus an increase in the speed of the fluid—implying an increase in its kinetic energy—occurs with a simultaneous decrease in (the sum of) its potential energy (including the static pressure) and internal energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the fluid is flowing out of a reservoir, the sum of all forms of energy is the same because in a reservoir the energy per unit volume (the sum of pressure and gravitational potential *ρ* *g* *h*) is the same everywhere.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle can also be derived directly from Isaac Newton's second law of motion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] When a fluid is flowing horizontally from a region of high pressure to a region of low pressure, there is more pressure from behind than in front.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] This gives a net force on the volume, accelerating it along the streamline.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Fluid particles are subject only to pressure and their own weight.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Consequently, within a fluid flowing horizontally, the highest speed occurs where the pressure is lowest, and the lowest speed occurs where the pressure is highest.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle is only applicable for isentropic flows: when the effects of irreversible processes (like turbulence) and non-adiabatic processes (e.g. thermal radiation) are small and can be neglected.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] However, the principle can be applied to various types of flow within these bounds, resulting in various forms of Bernoulli's equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The simple form of Bernoulli's equation is valid for incompressible flows (e.g. most liquid flows and gases moving at low Mach number).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] More advanced forms may be applied to compressible flows at higher Mach numbers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In most flows of liquids, and of gases at low Mach number, the density of a fluid parcel can be considered to be constant, regardless of pressure variations in the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Therefore, the fluid can be considered to be incompressible, and these flows are called incompressible flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli performed his experiments on liquids, so his equation in its original form is valid only for incompressible flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's equation and the Bernoulli constant are applicable throughout any region of flow where the energy per unit mass is uniform.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] For conservative force fields (not limited to the gravitational field), Bernoulli's equation can be generalized as: ${\frac {v^{2}}{2}}+\Psi +{\frac {p}{\rho }}={\text{constant}}$ where Ψ is the force potential at the point considered.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] For example, for the Earth's gravity Ψ = *gz*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The constant in the Bernoulli equation can be normalized.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The above equations suggest there is a flow speed at which pressure is zero, and at even higher speeds the pressure is negative.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Most often, gases and liquids are not capable of negative absolute pressure, or even zero pressure, so clearly Bernoulli's equation ceases to be valid before zero pressure is reached.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In liquids—when the pressure becomes too low—cavitation occurs.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The above equations use a linear relationship between flow speed squared and pressure.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] At higher flow speeds in gases, or for sound waves in liquid, the changes in mass density become significant so that the assumption of constant density is invalid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In many applications of Bernoulli's equation, the change in the ρgz term is so small compared with the other terms that it can be ignored.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] For example, in the case of aircraft in flight, the change in height z is so small the ρgz term can be omitted.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] This allows the above equation to be presented in the following simplified form: $p+q=p_{0}$ where *p*0 is called ***total pressure***, and q is *dynamic pressure*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Many authors refer to the pressure p as static pressure to distinguish it from total pressure *p*0 and dynamic pressure q.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Static pressure + Dynamic pressure = Total pressure.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Every point in a steadily flowing fluid, regardless of the fluid speed at that point, has its own unique static pressure p and dynamic pressure q.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Their sum *p* + *q* is defined to be the total pressure *p*0.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The significance of Bernoulli's principle can now be summarized as "total pressure is constant in any region free of viscous forces".
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the fluid flow is brought to rest at some point, this point is called a stagnation point, and at this point the static pressure is equal to the stagnation pressure.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the fluid flow is irrotational, the total pressure is uniform and Bernoulli's principle can be summarized as "total pressure is constant everywhere in the fluid flow".
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is reasonable to assume that irrotational flow exists in any situation where a large body of fluid is flowing past a solid body.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Examples are aircraft in flight and ships moving in open bodies of water.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] However, Bernoulli's principle importantly does not apply in the boundary layer such as in flow through long pipes.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The Bernoulli equation for unsteady potential flow is used in the theory of ocean surface waves and acoustics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] For an irrotational flow, the flow velocity can be described as the gradient ∇*φ* of a velocity potential φ.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] which is a Bernoulli equation valid also for unsteady—or time dependent—flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Here ⁠∂*φ*/∂*t*⁠ denotes the partial derivative of the velocity potential φ with respect to time t, and *v* = |∇*φ*| is the flow speed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The function *f*(*t*) depends only on time and not on position in the fluid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] As a result, the Bernoulli equation at some moment t applies in the whole fluid domain.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] This is also true for the special case of a steady irrotational flow, in which case f and ⁠∂*φ*/∂*t*⁠ are constants so equation (**A**) can be applied in every point of the fluid domain.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Note that the relation of the potential to the flow velocity is unaffected by this transformation: ∇Φ = ∇*φ*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The Bernoulli equation for unsteady potential flow also appears to play a central role in Luke's variational principle, a variational description of free-surface flows using the Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli developed his principle from observations on liquids, and Bernoulli's equation is valid for ideal fluids: those that are inviscid, incompressible and subjected only to conservative forces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is sometimes valid for the flow of gases as well, provided that there is no transfer of kinetic or potential energy from the gas flow to the compression or expansion of the gas.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] If both the gas pressure and volume change simultaneously, then work will be done on or by the gas.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In this case, Bernoulli's equation in its incompressible flow form cannot be assumed to be valid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] However, if the gas process is entirely isobaric, or isochoric, then no work is done on or by the gas (so the simple energy balance is not upset).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] According to the gas law, an isobaric or isochoric process is ordinarily the only way to ensure constant density in a gas.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Also the gas density will be proportional to the ratio of pressure and absolute temperature; however, this ratio will vary upon compression or expansion, no matter what non-zero quantity of heat is added or removed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The only exception is if the net heat transfer is zero, as in a complete thermodynamic cycle or in an individual isentropic (frictionless adiabatic) process, and even then this reversible process must be reversed, to restore the gas to the original pressure and specific volume, and thus density.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Only then is the original, unmodified Bernoulli equation applicable.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In this case the equation can be used if the flow speed of the gas is sufficiently below the speed of sound, such that the variation in density of the gas (due to this effect) along each streamline can be ignored.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Adiabatic flow at less than Mach 0.3 is generally considered to be slow enough.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is possible to use the fundamental principles of physics to develop similar equations applicable to compressible fluids.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] There are numerous equations, each tailored for a particular application, but all are analogous to Bernoulli's equation and all rely on nothing more than the fundamental principles of physics such as Newton's laws of motion or the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In engineering situations, elevations are generally small compared to the size of the Earth, and the time scales of fluid flow are small enough to consider the equation of state as adiabatic.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In many applications of compressible flow, changes in elevation are negligible compared to the other terms, so the term gz can be omitted.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Here w is the enthalpy per unit mass (also known as specific enthalpy), which is also often written as h (not to be confused with "head" or "height").
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Note that $w=e+{\frac {p}{\rho }}~~~\left(={\frac {\gamma }{\gamma -1}}{\frac {p}{\rho }}\right)$ where e is the thermodynamic energy per unit mass, also known as the specific internal energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] So, for constant internal energy e the equation reduces to the incompressible-flow form.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The constant on the right-hand side is often called the Bernoulli constant and denoted b.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] For steady inviscid adiabatic flow with no additional sources or sinks of energy, b is constant along any given streamline.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] More generally, when b may vary along streamlines, it still proves a useful parameter, related to the "head" of the fluid (see below).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] When the change in Ψ can be ignored, a very useful form of this equation is: ${\frac {v^{2}}{2}}+w=w_{0}$ where *w*0 is total enthalpy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] For a calorically perfect gas such as an ideal gas, the enthalpy is directly proportional to the temperature, and this leads to the concept of the total (or stagnation) temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] When shock waves are present, in a reference frame in which the shock is stationary and the flow is steady, many of the parameters in the Bernoulli equation suffer abrupt changes in passing through the shock.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The Bernoulli parameter remains unaffected.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] An exception to this rule is radiative shocks, which violate the assumptions leading to the Bernoulli equation, namely the lack of additional sinks or sources of energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] With the irrotational assumption, namely, the flow velocity can be described as the gradient ∇*φ* of a velocity potential *φ*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The Bernoulli equation for incompressible fluids can be derived by either integrating Newton's second law of motion or by applying the law of conservation of energy, ignoring viscosity, compressibility, and thermal effects.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The simplest derivation is to first ignore gravity and consider constrictions and expansions in pipes that are otherwise straight, as seen in Venturi effect.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Let the x axis be directed down the axis of the pipe.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Define a parcel of fluid moving through a pipe with cross-sectional area A, the length of the parcel is d*x*, and the volume of the parcel *A* d*x*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] If mass density is ρ, the mass of the parcel is density multiplied by its volume *m* = *ρA* d*x*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The change in pressure over distance d*x* is d*p* and flow velocity *v* = ⁠d*x*/d*t*⁠.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Apply Newton's second law of motion (force = mass × acceleration) and recognizing that the effective force on the parcel of fluid is −*A* d*p*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the pressure decreases along the length of the pipe, d*p* is negative but the force resulting in flow is positive along the x axis.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In steady flow the velocity field is constant with respect to time, *v* = *v*(*x*) = *v*(*x*(*t*)), so v itself is not directly a function of time t.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] With density ρ constant, the equation of motion can be written as ${\frac {\mathrm {d} }{\mathrm {d} x}}\left(\rho {\frac {v^{2}}{2}}+p\right)=0$ by integrating with respect to x ${\frac {v^{2}}{2}}+{\frac {p}{\rho }}=C$ where C is a constant, sometimes referred to as the Bernoulli constant.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is not a universal constant, but rather a constant of a particular fluid system.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The deduction is: where the speed is large, pressure is low and vice versa.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In the above derivation, no external work–energy principle is invoked.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Rather, Bernoulli's principle was derived by a simple manipulation of Newton's second law.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Another way to derive Bernoulli's principle for an incompressible flow is by applying conservation of energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The system consists of the volume of fluid, initially between the cross-sections *A*1 and *A*2.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In the time interval Δ*t* fluid elements initially at the inflow cross-section *A*1 move over a distance *s*1 = *v*1 Δ*t*, while at the outflow cross-section the fluid moves away from cross-section *A*2 over a distance *s*2 = *v*2 Δ*t*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The displaced fluid volumes at the inflow and outflow are respectively *A*1*s*1 and *A*2*s*2.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The associated displaced fluid masses are – when ρ is the fluid's mass density – equal to density times volume, so *ρA*1*s*1 and *ρA*2*s*2.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Further division by g produces the following equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Note that each term can be described in the length dimension (such as meters).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The middle term, z, represents the potential energy of the fluid due to its elevation with respect to a reference plane.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Now, z is called the elevation head and given the designation *z*elevation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] A free falling mass from an elevation *z* > 0 (in a vacuum) will reach a speed $v={\sqrt {{2g}{z}}},$ when arriving at elevation *z* = 0.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Or when rearranged as *head*: $h_{v}={\frac {v^{2}}{2g}}$ The term ⁠*v*2/2*g*⁠ is called the *velocity head*, expressed as a length measurement.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] It represents the internal energy of the fluid due to its motion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The hydrostatic pressure *p* is defined as $p=p_{0}-\rho gz,$ with *p*0 some reference pressure, or when rearranged as *head*: $\psi ={\frac {p}{\rho g}}.$ The term ⁠*p*/*ρg*⁠ is also called the *pressure head*, expressed as a length measurement.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] It represents the internal energy of the fluid due to the pressure exerted on the container.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The head due to the flow speed and the head due to static pressure combined with the elevation above a reference plane, a simple relationship useful for incompressible fluids using the velocity head, elevation head, and pressure head is obtained.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Note that the pressure of the system is constant in this form of the Bernoulli equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the static pressure of the system (the third term) increases, and if the pressure due to elevation (the middle term) is constant, then the dynamic pressure (the first term) must have decreased.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In other words, if the speed of a fluid decreases and it is not due to an elevation difference, it must be due to an increase in the static pressure that is resisting the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] All three equations are merely simplified versions of an energy balance on a system.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] The derivation for compressible fluids is similar.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Again, the derivation depends upon (1) conservation of mass, and (2) conservation of energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Clearly, in a more complicated situation such as a fluid flow coupled with radiation, such conditions are not met.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Nevertheless, assuming this to be the case and assuming the flow is steady so that the net change in the energy is zero, $\Delta E_{1}-\Delta E_{2}=0$ where Δ*E*1 and Δ*E*2 are the energy entering through *A*1 and leaving through *A*2, respectively.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] A similar expression for Δ*E*2 may easily be constructed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In modern everyday life there are many observations that can be successfully explained by application of Bernoulli's principle, even though no real fluid is entirely inviscid, and a small viscosity often has a large effect on the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle is then cited to conclude that the pressure on top of the wing must be lower than on the bottom.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Equal transit time applies to the flow around a body generating no lift, but there is no physical principle that requires equal transit time in cases of bodies generating lift.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] In fact, theory predicts – and experiments confirm – that the air traverses the top surface of a body experiencing lift in a *shorter* time than it traverses the bottom surface; the explanation based on equal transit time is false.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] While the equal-time explanation is false, it is not the Bernoulli principle that is false, because this principle is well established; Bernoulli's equation is used correctly in common mathematical treatments of aerodynamic lift.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] There are several common classroom demonstrations that are sometimes incorrectly explained using Bernoulli's principle.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] One involves holding a piece of paper horizontally so that it droops downward and then blowing over the top of it.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] As the demonstrator blows over the paper, the paper rises.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is then asserted that this is because "faster moving air has lower pressure".
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] One problem with this explanation can be seen by blowing along the bottom of the paper: if the deflection was caused by faster moving air, then the paper should deflect downward; but the paper deflects upward regardless of whether the faster moving air is on the top or the bottom.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] A third problem is that it is false to make a connection between the flow on the two sides of the paper using Bernoulli's equation since the air above and below are *different* flow fields and Bernoulli's principle only applies within a flow field.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] As the wording of the principle can change its implications, stating the principle correctly is important.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] What Bernoulli's principle actually says is that within a flow of constant energy, when fluid flows through a region of lower pressure it speeds up and vice versa.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Thus, Bernoulli's principle concerns itself with *changes* in speed and *changes* in pressure *within* a flow field.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] It cannot be used to compare different flow fields.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] A correct explanation of why the paper rises would observe that the plume follows the curve of the paper and that a curved streamline will develop a pressure gradient perpendicular to the direction of flow, with the lower pressure on the inside of the curve.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle predicts that the decrease in pressure is associated with an increase in speed; in other words, as the air passes over the paper, it speeds up and moves faster than it was moving when it left the demonstrator's mouth.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] But this is not apparent from the demonstration.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/bernoulli-s-principle] Other common classroom demonstrations, such as blowing between two suspended spheres, inflating a large bag, or suspending a ball in an airstream are sometimes explained in a similarly misleading manner by saying "faster moving air has lower pressure".
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In physics and fluid mechanics, a **boundary layer** is the thin layer of fluid in the immediate vicinity of a bounding surface formed by the fluid flowing along the surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The fluid's interaction with the wall induces a no-slip boundary condition (zero velocity at the wall).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The flow velocity then monotonically increases above the surface until it returns to the bulk flow velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The thin layer consisting of fluid whose velocity has not yet returned to the bulk flow velocity is called the velocity boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The air next to a human is heated, resulting in gravity-induced convective airflow, which results in both a velocity and thermal boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] A breeze disrupts the boundary layer, and hair and clothing protect it, making the human feel cooler or warmer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] On an aircraft wing, the velocity boundary layer is the part of the flow close to the wing, where viscous forces distort the surrounding non-viscous flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In the Earth's atmosphere, the atmospheric boundary layer is the air layer (~ 1 km) near the ground.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] It is affected by the surface; day-night heat flows caused by the sun heating the ground, moisture, or momentum transfer to or from the surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Laminar boundary layers can be loosely classified according to their structure and the circumstances under which they are created.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] When a fluid rotates and viscous forces are balanced by the Coriolis effect (rather than convective inertia), an Ekman layer forms.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In the theory of heat transfer, a thermal boundary layer occurs.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] A surface can have multiple types of boundary layer simultaneously.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The viscous nature of airflow reduces the local velocities on a surface and is responsible for skin friction.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The layer of air over the wing's surface that is slowed down or stopped by viscosity, is the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] There are two different types of boundary layer flow: laminar and turbulent.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The laminar boundary is a very smooth flow, while the turbulent boundary layer contains swirls or "eddies." The laminar flow creates less skin friction drag than the turbulent flow, but is less stable.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Boundary layer flow over a wing surface begins as a smooth laminar flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] As the flow continues back from the leading edge, the laminar boundary layer increases in thickness.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] At some distance back from the leading edge, the smooth laminar flow breaks down and transitions to a turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] From a drag standpoint, it is advisable to have the transition from laminar to turbulent flow as far aft on the wing as possible, or have a large amount of the wing surface within the laminar portion of the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The low energy laminar flow, however, tends to break down more suddenly than the turbulent layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The aerodynamic boundary layer was first hypothesized by Ludwig Prandtl in a paper presented on August 12, 1904, at the third International Congress of Mathematicians in Heidelberg, Germany.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This allows a closed-form solution for the flow in both areas by making significant simplifications of the full Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The same hypothesis is applicable to other fluids (besides air) with moderate to low viscosity such as water.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] For the case where there is a temperature difference between the surface and the bulk fluid, it is found that the majority of the heat transfer to and from a body takes place in the vicinity of the velocity boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This again allows the equations to be simplified in the flow field outside the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The pressure distribution throughout the boundary layer in the direction normal to the surface (such as an airfoil) remains relatively constant throughout the boundary layer, and is the same as on the surface itself.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The thickness of the velocity boundary layer is normally defined as the distance from the solid body to the point at which the viscous flow velocity is 99% of the freestream velocity (the surface velocity of an inviscid flow).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Displacement thickness is an alternative definition stating that the boundary layer represents a deficit in mass flow compared to inviscid flow with slip at the wall.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] It is the distance by which the wall would have to be displaced in the inviscid case to give the same total mass flow as the viscous case.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The no-slip condition requires the flow velocity at the surface of a solid object be zero and the fluid temperature be equal to the temperature of the surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The flow velocity will then increase rapidly within the boundary layer, governed by the boundary layer equations, below.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The thermal boundary layer thickness is similarly the distance from the body at which the temperature is 99% of the freestream temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The ratio of the two thicknesses is governed by the Prandtl number.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is 1, the two boundary layers are the same thickness.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is greater than 1, the thermal boundary layer is thinner than the velocity boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] If the Prandtl number is less than 1, which is the case for air at standard conditions, the thermal boundary layer is thicker than the velocity boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In high-performance designs, such as gliders and commercial aircraft, much attention is paid to controlling the behavior of the boundary layer to minimize drag.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] First, the boundary layer adds to the effective thickness of the body, through the displacement thickness, hence increasing the pressure drag.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Secondly, the shear forces at the surface of the wing create skin friction drag.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] At high Reynolds numbers, typical of full-sized aircraft, it is desirable to have a laminar boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This results in a lower skin friction due to the characteristic velocity profile of laminar flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] However, the boundary layer inevitably thickens and becomes less stable as the flow develops along the body, and eventually becomes turbulent, the process known as boundary layer transition.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] One way of dealing with this problem is to suck the boundary layer away through a porous surface (see Boundary layer suction).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This can reduce drag, but is usually impractical due to its mechanical complexity and the power required to move the air and dispose of it.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Natural laminar flow (NLF) techniques push the boundary layer transition aft by reshaping the airfoil or fuselage so that its thickest point is more aft and less thick.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This reduces the velocities in the leading part and the same Reynolds number is achieved with a greater length.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] At lower Reynolds numbers, such as those seen with model aircraft, it is relatively easy to maintain laminar flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This gives low skin friction, which is desirable.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] However, the same velocity profile which gives the laminar boundary layer its low skin friction also causes it to be badly affected by adverse pressure gradients.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] As the pressure begins to recover over the rear part of the wing chord, a laminar boundary layer will tend to separate from the surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Such flow separation causes a large increase in the pressure drag, since it greatly increases the effective size of the wing section.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In these cases, it can be advantageous to deliberately trip the boundary layer into turbulence at a point prior to the location of laminar separation, using a turbulator.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The fuller velocity profile of the turbulent boundary layer allows it to sustain the adverse pressure gradient without separating.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Thus, although the skin friction is increased, overall drag is decreased.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This is the principle behind the dimpling on golf balls, as well as vortex generators on aircraft.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Special wing sections have also been designed which tailor the pressure recovery so laminar separation is reduced or even eliminated.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This represents an optimum compromise between the pressure drag from flow separation and skin friction from induced turbulence.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] When using half-models in wind tunnels, a peniche is sometimes used to reduce or eliminate the effect of the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The deduction of the **boundary layer equations** was one of the most important advances in fluid dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Using an order of magnitude analysis, the well-known governing Navier–Stokes equations of viscous fluid flow can be greatly simplified within the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Notably, the characteristic of the partial differential equations (PDE) becomes parabolic, rather than the elliptical form of the full Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This greatly simplifies the solution of the equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] By making the boundary layer approximation, the flow is divided into an inviscid portion (which is easy to solve by a number of methods) and the boundary layer, which is governed by an easier to solve PDE.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] where u and $\upsilon$ are the velocity components, $\rho$ is the density, p is the pressure, and $\nu$ is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid at a point.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The approximation states that, for a sufficiently high Reynolds number the flow over a surface can be divided into an outer region of inviscid flow unaffected by viscosity (the majority of the flow), and a region close to the surface where viscosity is important (the boundary layer).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Let u and $\upsilon$ be streamwise and transverse (wall normal) velocities respectively inside the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The order of magnitude analysis assumes the streamwise length scale significantly larger than the transverse length scale inside the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] It follows that variations in properties in the streamwise direction are generally much lower than those in the wall normal direction.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Apply this to the continuity equation shows that $\upsilon$ , the wall normal velocity, is small compared with u the streamwise velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Since the static pressure p is independent of y , then pressure at the edge of the boundary layer is the pressure throughout the boundary layer at a given streamwise position.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The external pressure may be obtained through an application of Bernoulli's equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Let U be the fluid velocity outside the boundary layer, where u and U are both parallel.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] These approximations are used in a variety of practical flow problems of scientific and engineering interest.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The above analysis is for any instantaneous laminar or turbulent boundary layer, but is used mainly in laminar flow studies since the mean flow is also the instantaneous flow because there are no velocity fluctuations present.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This simplified equation is a parabolic PDE and can be solved using a similarity solution often referred to as the Blasius boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Since the solution is not unique from mathematical perspective, to the solution can be added any one of an infinite set of eigenfunctions as shown by Stewartson and Paul A.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Von Kármán derived the integral equation by integrating the boundary layer equation across the boundary layer in 1921.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The energy integral was derived by Wieghardt.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] For steady two-dimensional boundary layers, von Mises introduced a transformation which takes x and $\psi$ (stream function) as independent variables instead of x and y and uses a dependent variable $\chi =U^{2}-u^{2}$ instead of u .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This transformation is later extended to compressible boundary layer by von Kármán and HS Tsien.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] For steady two-dimensional compressible boundary layer, Luigi Crocco introduced a transformation which takes x and u as independent variables instead of x and y and uses a dependent variable $\tau =\mu \partial u/\partial y$ (shear stress) instead of u .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The treatment of turbulent boundary layers is far more difficult due to the time-dependent variation of the flow properties.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] One of the most widely used techniques in which turbulent flows are tackled is to apply Reynolds decomposition.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Here the instantaneous flow properties are decomposed into a mean and fluctuating component with the assumption that the mean of the fluctuating component is always zero.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Using a similar order-of-magnitude analysis, the above equations can be reduced to leading order terms.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This equation does not satisfy the no-slip condition at the wall.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Like Prandtl did for his boundary layer equations, a new, smaller length scale must be used to allow the viscous term to become leading order in the momentum equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In the limit of infinite Reynolds number, the pressure gradient term can be shown to have no effect on the inner region of the turbulent boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The new "inner length scale" $\eta$ is a viscous length scale, and is of order ${\frac {\nu }{u_{*}}}$ , with $u_{*}$ being the velocity scale of the turbulent fluctuations, in this case a friction velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Unlike the laminar boundary layer equations, the presence of two regimes governed by different sets of flow scales (i.e. the inner and outer scaling) has made finding a universal similarity solution for the turbulent boundary layer difficult and controversial.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] To find a similarity solution that spans both regions of the flow, it is necessary to asymptotically match the solutions from both regions of the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Such analysis will yield either the so-called log-law or power-law.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Similar approaches to the above analysis has also been applied for thermal boundary layers, using the energy equation in compressible flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The additional term ${\overline {u'v'}}$ in the turbulent boundary layer equations is known as the Reynolds shear stress and is unknown a priori.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The solution of the turbulent boundary layer equations therefore necessitates the use of a turbulence model, which aims to express the Reynolds shear stress in terms of known flow variables or derivatives.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The lack of accuracy and generality of such models is a major obstacle in the successful prediction of turbulent flow properties in modern fluid dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] A constant stress layer exists in the near wall region.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Due to the damping of the vertical velocity fluctuations near the wall, the Reynolds stress term will become negligible and we find that a linear velocity profile exists.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This is only true for the very near wall region.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In 1928, the French engineer André Lévêque observed that convective heat transfer in a flowing fluid is affected only by the velocity values very close to the surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] For flows of large Prandtl number, the temperature/mass transition from surface to freestream temperature takes place across a very thin region close to the surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Therefore, the most important fluid velocities are those inside this very thin region in which the change in velocity can be considered linear with normal distance from the surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] where *θ* is the tangent of the Poiseuille parabola intersecting the wall.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Although Lévêque's solution was specific to heat transfer into a Poiseuille flow, his insight helped lead other scientists to an exact solution of the thermal boundary-layer problem.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Schuh observed that in a boundary-layer, *u* is again a linear function of *y*, but that in this case, the wall tangent is a function of *x*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This results in a very good approximation, even for low $Pr$ numbers, so that only liquid metals with $Pr$ much less than 1 cannot be treated this way.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In 1962, Kestin and Persen published a paper describing solutions for heat transfer when the thermal boundary layer is contained entirely within the momentum layer and for various wall temperature distributions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] For the problem of a flat plate with a temperature jump at $x=x_{0}$ , they propose a substitution that reduces the parabolic thermal boundary-layer equation to an ordinary differential equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The solution to this equation, the temperature at any point in the fluid, can be expressed as an incomplete gamma function.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Schlichting proposed an equivalent substitution that reduces the thermal boundary-layer equation to an ordinary differential equation whose solution is the same incomplete gamma function.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Analytic solutions can be derived with the time-dependent self-similar Ansatz for the incompressible boundary layer equations including heat conduction.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] As is well known from several textbooks, heat transfer tends to decrease with the increase in the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Recently, it was observed on a practical and large scale that wind flowing through a photovoltaic generator tends to "trap" heat in the PV panels under a turbulent regime due to the decrease in heat transfer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Paul Richard Heinrich Blasius derived an exact solution to the above laminar boundary layer equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The thickness of the boundary layer $\delta$ is a function of the Reynolds number for laminar flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Note that in many cases, the no-slip boundary condition holds that $v_{S}$ , the fluid velocity at the surface of the plate equals the velocity of the plate at all locations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] If the plate is not moving, then $v_{S}=0$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] A much more complicated derivation is required if fluid slip is allowed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In fact, the Blasius solution for laminar velocity profile in the boundary layer above a semi-infinite plate can be easily extended to describe Thermal and Concentration boundary layers for heat and mass transfer respectively.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] For the momentum balance, kinematic viscosity $\nu$ can be considered to be the *momentum diffusivity*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In the energy balance this is replaced by thermal diffusivity $\alpha ={k/\rho C_{P}}$ , and by mass diffusivity $D_{AB}$ in the mass balance.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] In thermal diffusivity of a substance, k is its thermal conductivity, $\rho$ is its density and $C_{P}$ is its heat capacity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Subscript AB denotes diffusivity of species A diffusing into species B.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Under the assumption that $\alpha =D_{AB}=\nu$ , these equations become equivalent to the momentum balance.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Thus, for Prandtl number $Pr=\nu /\alpha =1$ and Schmidt number $Sc=\nu /D_{AB}=1$ the Blasius solution applies directly.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Accordingly, this derivation uses a related form of the boundary conditions, replacing v with T or $c_{A}$ (absolute temperature or concentration of species A).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The subscript S denotes a surface condition.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Using the streamline function Blasius obtained the following solution for the shear stress at the surface of the plate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] where $\delta _{T},\delta _{c}$ are the regions of flow where T and $c_{A}$ are less than 99% of their far field values.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Because the Prandtl number of a particular fluid is not often unity, German engineer E.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Polhausen who worked with Ludwig Prandtl attempted to empirically extend these equations to apply for $Pr\neq 1$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] His results can be applied to $Sc$ as well.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] From this solution, it is possible to characterize the convective heat/mass transfer constants based on the region of boundary layer flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Fourier's law of conduction and Newton's Law of Cooling are combined with the flux term derived above and the boundary layer thickness.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This gives the local convective constant $h_{x}$ at one point on the semi-infinite plane.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] These solutions apply for laminar flow with a Prandtl/Schmidt number greater than 0.6.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Many of the principles that apply to aircraft also apply to ships, submarines, and offshore platforms, with water as the primary fluid of concern rather than air.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] As water is not an ideal fluid, ships moving in water experience resistance.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] While the front of the ship faces normal pressure forces due to the fluid surrounding it, the aft portion sees a lower acting component of pressure due to the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This leads to higher resistance due to pressure known as 'viscous pressure drag' or 'form drag'.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] For ships, unlike aircraft, one deals with incompressible flows, where change in water density is negligible (a pressure rise close to 1000kPa leads to a change of only 2–3 kg/m3).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This field of fluid dynamics is called hydrodynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] A ship engineer designs for hydrodynamics first, and for strength only later.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] The boundary layer development, breakdown, and separation become critical because the high viscosity of water produces high shear stresses.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] This effect was exploited in the Tesla turbine, patented by Nikola Tesla in 1913.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] It is referred to as a bladeless turbine because it uses the boundary layer effect and not a fluid impinging upon the blades as in a conventional turbine.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Boundary layer turbines are also known as cohesion-type turbine, bladeless turbine, and Prandtl layer turbine (after Ludwig Prandtl).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] By using the transient and viscous force equations for a cylindrical flow you can predict the transient boundary layer thickness by finding the Womersley Number ( $N_{w}$ ).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] where $N_{w}$ = Womersley Number; $\rho$ = density; v = velocity; $w=$ frequency of oscillations; $\delta _{1}$ = length of transient boundary layer; $\mu$ = viscosity; L = characteristic length.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] By using the convective and viscous force equations at the boundary layer for a cylindrical flow you can predict the convective flow conditions at the boundary layer by finding the dimensionless Reynolds Number ( $Re$ ).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] where $Re$ = Reynolds Number; $\rho$ = density; v = velocity; $\delta _{2}$ = length of convective boundary layer; $\mu$ = viscosity; L = characteristic length.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Boundary layer ingestion promises an increase in aircraft fuel efficiency with an aft-mounted propulsor ingesting the slow fuselage boundary layer and re-energising the wake to reduce drag and improve propulsive efficiency.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] To operate in distorted airflow, the fan is heavier and its efficiency is reduced, and its integration is challenging.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] It is used in concepts like the Aurora D8 or the French research agency Onera's Nova, saving 5% in cruise by ingesting 40% of the fuselage boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Airbus presented the Nautilius concept at the ICAS congress in September 2018: to ingest all the fuselage boundary layer, while minimizing the azimuthal flow distortion, the fuselage splits into two spindles with 13-18:1 bypass ratio fans.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] Propulsive efficiencies are up to 90% like counter-rotating open rotors with smaller, lighter, less complex and noisy engines.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/boundary-layer] It could lower fuel burn by over 10% compared to a usual underwing 15:1 bypass ratio engine.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The study of gas dynamics is often associated with the flight of modern high-speed aircraft and atmospheric reentry of space-exploration vehicles; however, its origins lie with simpler machines.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] At the beginning of the 19th century, investigation into the behaviour of fired bullets led to improvement in the accuracy and capabilities of guns and artillery.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] As the century progressed, inventors such as Gustaf de Laval advanced the field, while researchers such as Ernst Mach sought to understand the physical phenomena involved through experimentation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] At the beginning of the 20th century, the focus of gas dynamics research shifted to what would eventually become the aerospace industry.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Ludwig Prandtl and his students proposed important concepts ranging from the boundary layer to supersonic shock waves, supersonic wind tunnels, and supersonic nozzle design.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Theodore von Kármán, a student of Prandtl, continued to improve the understanding of supersonic flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Other notable figures (Meyer, Luigi Crocco, and Ascher Shapiro) also contributed significantly to the principles considered fundamental to the study of modern gas dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Many others also contributed to this field.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Amongst other factors, conventional aerofoils saw a dramatic increase in drag coefficient when the flow approached the speed of sound.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Overcoming the larger drag proved difficult with contemporary designs, thus the perception of a sound barrier.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] However, aircraft design progressed sufficiently to produce the Bell X-1.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Piloted by Chuck Yeager, the X-1 officially achieved supersonic speed in October 1947.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Historically, two parallel paths of research have been followed in order to further gas dynamics knowledge.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Experimental gas dynamics undertakes wind tunnel model experiments and experiments in shock tubes and ballistic ranges with the use of optical techniques to document the findings.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Theoretical gas dynamics considers the equations of motion applied to a variable-density gas, and their solutions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Much of basic gas dynamics is analytical, but in the modern era Computational fluid dynamics applies computing power to solve the otherwise-intractable nonlinear partial differential equations of compressible flow for specific geometries and flow characteristics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] There are several important assumptions involved in the underlying theory of compressible flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] All fluids are composed of molecules, but tracking a huge number of individual molecules in a flow (for example at atmospheric pressure) is unnecessary.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Instead, the continuum assumption allows us to consider a flowing gas as a continuous substance except at low densities.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This assumption provides a huge simplification which is accurate for most gas-dynamic problems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Only in the low-density realm of rarefied gas dynamics does the motion of individual molecules become important.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] A related assumption is the no-slip condition where the flow velocity at a solid surface is presumed equal to the velocity of the surface itself, which is a direct consequence of assuming continuum flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The no-slip condition implies that the flow is viscous, and as a result a boundary layer forms on bodies traveling through the air at high speeds, much as it does in low-speed flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Most problems in incompressible flow involve only two unknowns: pressure and velocity, which are typically found by solving the two equations that describe conservation of mass and of linear momentum, with the fluid density presumed constant.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] In compressible flow, however, the gas density and temperature also become variables.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This requires two more equations in order to solve compressible-flow problems: an equation of state for the gas and a conservation of energy equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] For the majority of gas-dynamic problems, the simple ideal gas law is the appropriate state equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Otherwise, more complex equations of state must be considered and the so-called non ideal compressible fluids dynamics (NICFD) establishes.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Fluid dynamics problems have two overall types of references frames, called Lagrangian and Eulerian (see Joseph-Louis Lagrange and Leonhard Euler).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The Lagrangian approach follows a fluid mass of fixed identity as it moves through a flowfield.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The Eulerian reference frame, in contrast, does not move with the fluid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Rather it is a fixed frame or control volume that fluid flows through.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The Eulerian frame is most useful in a majority of compressible flow problems, but requires that the equations of motion be written in a compatible format.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Finally, although space is known to have 3 dimensions, an important simplification can be had in describing gas dynamics mathematically if only one spatial dimension is of primary importance, hence 1-dimensional flow is assumed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This works well in duct, nozzle, and diffuser flows where the flow properties change mainly in the flow direction rather than perpendicular to the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] However, an important class of compressible flows, including the external flow over bodies traveling at high speed, requires at least a 2-dimensional treatment.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] When all 3 spatial dimensions and perhaps the time dimension as well are important, we often resort to computerized solutions of the governing equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The Mach number (M) is defined as the ratio of the speed of an object (or of a flow) to the speed of sound.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] For instance, in air at room temperature, the speed of sound is about 343 m/s (1,130 ft/s).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] M can range from 0 to ∞, but this broad range falls naturally into several flow regimes.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] These regimes are subsonic, transonic, supersonic, hypersonic, and hypervelocity flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The figure below illustrates the Mach number "spectrum" of these flow regimes.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] These flow regimes are not chosen arbitrarily, but rather arise naturally from the strong mathematical background that underlies compressible flow (see the cited reference textbooks).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] At very slow flow speeds the speed of sound is so much faster that it is mathematically ignored, and the Mach number is irrelevant.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Once the speed of the flow approaches the speed of sound, however, the Mach number becomes all-important, and shock waves begin to appear.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Thus the transonic regime is described by a different (and much more complex) mathematical treatment.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] In the supersonic regime the flow is dominated by wave motion at oblique angles similar to the Mach angle.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Above about Mach 5, these wave angles grow so small that a different mathematical approach is required, defining the hypersonic speed regime.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Finally, at speeds comparable to that of planetary atmospheric entry from orbit, in the range of several km/s, the speed of sound is now comparatively so slow that it is once again mathematically ignored in the hypervelocity regime.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] As an object accelerates from subsonic toward supersonic speed in a gas, different types of wave phenomena occur.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] To illustrate these changes, the next figure shows a stationary point (M = 0) that emits symmetric sound waves.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The speed of sound is the same in all directions in a uniform fluid, so these waves are simply concentric spheres.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] As the sound-generating point begins to accelerate, the sound waves "bunch up" in the direction of motion and "stretch out" in the opposite direction.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] When the point reaches sonic speed (M = 1), it travels at the same speed as the sound waves it creates.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Therefore, an infinite number of these sound waves "pile up" ahead of the point, forming a Shock wave.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Upon achieving supersonic flow, the particle is moving so fast that it continuously leaves its sound waves behind.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] where a represents the speed of sound in the gas and V represents the velocity of the object.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Although named for Austrian physicist Ernst Mach, these oblique waves were first discovered by Christian Doppler.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] One-dimensional (1-D) flow refers to flow of gas through a duct or channel in which the flow parameters are assumed to change significantly along only one spatial dimension, namely, the duct length.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] As the speed of a flow accelerates from the subsonic to the supersonic regime, the physics of nozzle and diffuser flows is altered.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] where dP is the differential change in pressure, M is the Mach number, ρ is the density of the gas, V is the velocity of the flow, A is the area of the duct, and dA is the change in area of the duct.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This equation states that, for subsonic flow, a converging duct (dA < 0) increases the velocity of the flow and a diverging duct (dA > 0) decreases velocity of the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] For supersonic flow, the opposite occurs due to the change of sign of (1 − M2).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] A converging duct (dA < 0) now decreases the velocity of the flow and a diverging duct (dA > 0) increases the velocity of the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] At Mach = 1, a special case occurs in which the duct area must be either a maximum or minimum.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] For practical purposes, only a minimum area can accelerate flows to Mach 1 and beyond.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] See table of sub-supersonic diffusers and nozzles.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Therefore, to accelerate a flow to Mach 1, a nozzle must be designed to converge to a minimum cross-sectional area and then expand.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This type of nozzle – the converging-diverging nozzle – is called a de Laval nozzle after Gustaf de Laval, who invented it.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] As subsonic flow enters the converging duct and the area decreases, the flow accelerates.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Upon reaching the minimum area of the duct, also known as the throat of the nozzle, the flow can reach Mach 1.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] If the speed of the flow is to continue to increase, its density must decrease in order to obey conservation of mass.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] To achieve this decrease in density, the flow must expand, and to do so, the flow must pass through a diverging duct.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Ultimately, because of the energy conservation law, a gas is limited to a certain maximum velocity based on its energy content.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] where cp is the specific heat of the gas and Tt is the stagnation temperature of the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] can be obtained, where M is the Mach number and γ is the ratio of specific heats (1.4 for air).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] See table of isentropic flow Mach number relationships.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] As previously mentioned, in order for a flow to become supersonic, it must pass through a duct with a minimum area, or sonic throat.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Additionally, an overall pressure ratio, Pb/Pt, of approximately 2 is needed to attain Mach 1.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Once it has reached Mach 1, the flow at the throat is said to be *choked*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Because changes downstream can only move upstream at sonic speed, the mass flow through the nozzle cannot be affected by changes in downstream conditions after the flow is choked.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Normal shock waves are shock waves that are perpendicular to the local flow direction.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] These shock waves occur when pressure waves build up and coalesce into an extremely thin shockwave that converts kinetic energy into thermal energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The waves thus overtake and reinforce one another, forming a finite shock wave from an infinite series of infinitesimal sound waves.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Because the change of state across the shock is highly irreversible, entropy increases across the shock.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] When analysing a normal shock wave, one-dimensional, steady, and adiabatic flow of a perfect gas is assumed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Stagnation temperature and stagnation enthalpy are the same upstream and downstream of the shock.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Normal shock waves can be easily analysed in either of two reference frames: the standing normal shock and the moving shock.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The flow before a normal shock wave must be supersonic, and the flow after a normal shock must be subsonic.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The Rankine-Hugoniot equations are used to solve for the flow conditions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Although one-dimensional flow can be directly analysed, it is merely a specialized case of two-dimensional flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] It follows that one of the defining phenomena of one-dimensional flow, a normal shock, is likewise only a special case of a larger class of oblique shocks.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Further, the name "normal" is with respect to geometry rather than frequency of occurrence.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Oblique shocks are much more common in applications such as: aircraft inlet design, objects in supersonic flight, and (at a more fundamental level) supersonic nozzles and diffusers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Depending on the flow conditions, an oblique shock can either be attached to the flow or detached from the flow in the form of a bow shock.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Oblique shock waves are similar to normal shock waves, but they occur at angles less than 90° with the direction of flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] When a disturbance is introduced to the flow at a nonzero angle (δ), the flow must respond to the changing boundary conditions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Thus an oblique shock is formed, resulting in a change in the direction of the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Based on the level of flow deflection (δ), oblique shocks are characterized as either strong or weak.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Strong shocks are characterized by larger deflection and more entropy loss across the shock, with weak shocks as the opposite.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] In order to gain cursory insight into the differences in these shocks, a shock polar diagram can be used.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] with R as the gas constant and γ as the specific heat ratio.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] with Vx and Vy as the x and y-components of the fluid velocity V.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] With the Mach number before the shock given, a locus of conditions can be specified.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] At some δmax, the flow transitions from a strong to weak oblique shock.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] With δ = 0°, a normal shock is produced at the limit of the strong oblique shock and the Mach wave is produced at the limit of the weak shock wave.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Due to the inclination of the shock, after an oblique shock is created, it can interact with a boundary in three different manners, two of which are explained below.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Incoming flow is first turned by angle δ with respect to the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This shockwave is reflected off the solid boundary, and the flow is turned by – δ to again be parallel with the boundary.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Each progressive shock wave is weaker, and the wave angle is increased.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] An irregular reflection is much like the case described above, with the caveat that δ is larger than the maximum allowable turning angle.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Thus, a detached shock is formed and a more complicated reflection known as Mach reflection occurs.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Prandtl–Meyer fans can be expressed as both compression and expansion fans.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Prandtl–Meyer fans also cross a boundary layer (i.e. flowing and solid) which reacts in different changes as well.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] When a shock wave hits a solid surface, the resulting fan returns as one from the opposite family while when one hits a free boundary the fan returns as a fan of opposite type.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] To this point, the only flow phenomena that have been discussed are shock waves, which slow the flow and increase its entropy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] It is possible to accelerate supersonic flow in what has been termed a Prandtl–Meyer expansion fan, after Ludwig Prandtl and Theodore Meyer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The mechanism for the expansion is shown in the figure below.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] As opposed to the flow encountering an inclined obstruction and forming an oblique shock, the flow expands around a convex corner and forms an expansion fan through a series of isentropic Mach waves.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The expansion "fan" is composed of Mach waves that span from the initial Mach angle to the final Mach angle.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Flow can expand around either a sharp or rounded corner equally, as the increase in Mach number is proportional to only the convex angle of the passage (δ).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The expansion corner that produces the Prandtl–Meyer fan can be sharp (as illustrated in the figure) or rounded.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] If the total turning angle is the same, then the P-M flow solution is also the same.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The Prandtl–Meyer expansion can be seen as the physical explanation of the operation of the Laval nozzle.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The contour of the nozzle creates a smooth and continuous series of Prandtl–Meyer expansion waves.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] A Prandtl–Meyer compression is the opposite phenomenon to a Prandtl–Meyer expansion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] If the flow is gradually turned through an angle of δ, a compression fan can be formed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This fan is a series of Mach waves that eventually coalesce into an oblique shock.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Because the flow is defined by an isentropic region (flow that travels through the fan) and an anisentropic region (flow that travels through the oblique shock), a slip line results between the two flow regions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Supersonic wind tunnels are used for testing and research in supersonic flows, approximately over the Mach number range of 1.2 to 5.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The operating principle behind the wind tunnel is that a large pressure difference is maintained upstream to downstream, driving the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Wind tunnels can be divided into two categories: continuous-operating and intermittent-operating wind tunnels.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Continuous operating supersonic wind tunnels require an independent electrical power source that drastically increases with the size of the test section.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Intermittent supersonic wind tunnels are less expensive in that they store electrical energy over an extended period of time, then discharge the energy over a series of brief tests.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The difference between these two is analogous to the comparison between a battery and a capacitor.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Blowdown type supersonic wind tunnels offer high Reynolds number, a small storage tank, and readily available dry air.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] However, they cause a high-pressure hazard, result in difficulty holding a constant stagnation pressure, and are noisy during operation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Indraft supersonic wind tunnels are not associated with a pressure hazard, allow a constant stagnation pressure, and are relatively quiet.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Unfortunately, they have a limited range for the Reynolds number of the flow and require a large vacuum tank.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] There is no dispute that knowledge is gained through research and testing in supersonic wind tunnels; however, the facilities often require vast amounts of power to maintain the large pressure ratios needed for testing conditions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] For example, Arnold Engineering Development Complex has the largest supersonic wind tunnel in the world and requires the power required to light a small city for operation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] For this reason, large wind tunnels are becoming less common at universities.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Perhaps the most common requirement for oblique shocks is in supersonic aircraft inlets for speeds greater than about Mach 2 (the F-16 has a maximum speed of Mach 2 but doesn't need an oblique shock intake).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] One purpose of the inlet is to minimize losses across the shocks as the incoming supersonic air slows down to subsonic before it enters the turbojet engine.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This is accomplished with one or more oblique shocks followed by a very weak normal shock, with an upstream Mach number usually less than 1.4.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] The airflow through the intake has to be managed correctly over a wide speed range from zero to its maximum supersonic speed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] This is done by varying the position of the intake surfaces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] Although variable geometry is required to achieve acceptable performance from take-off to speeds exceeding Mach 2 there is no one method to achieve it.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/compressible-flow] For example, for a maximum speed of about Mach 3, the XB-70 used rectangular inlets with adjustable ramps and the SR-71 used circular inlets with adjustable inlet cone.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In physics, physical chemistry, and engineering, **fluid dynamics** is a subdiscipline of fluid mechanics that describes the flow of fluids – liquids and gases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] It has several subdisciplines, including *aerodynamics* (the study of air and other gases in motion) and *hydrodynamics* (the study of water and other liquids in motion).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Fluid dynamics offers a systematic structure—which underlies these practical disciplines—that embraces empirical and semi-empirical laws derived from flow measurement and used to solve practical problems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The solution to a fluid dynamics problem typically involves the calculation of various properties of the fluid, such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, as functions of space and time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Before the twentieth century, "**hydrodynamics**" was synonymous with fluid dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] This is still reflected in names of some fluid dynamics topics, like magnetohydrodynamics and hydrodynamic stability, both of which can also be applied to gases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The foundational axioms of fluid dynamics are the conservation laws, specifically, conservation of mass, conservation of linear momentum, and conservation of energy (also known as the *first law of thermodynamics*).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] These are based on classical mechanics and are modified in quantum mechanics and general relativity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] They are expressed using the Reynolds transport theorem.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In addition to the above, fluids are assumed to obey the continuum assumption.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] At small scale, all fluids are composed of molecules that collide with one another and solid objects.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] However, the continuum assumption assumes that fluids are continuous, rather than discrete.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Consequently, it is assumed that properties such as density, pressure, temperature, and flow velocity are well-defined at infinitesimally small points in space and vary continuously from one point to another.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The fact that the fluid is made up of discrete molecules is ignored.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The unsimplified equations do not have a general closed-form solution, so they are primarily of use in computational fluid dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The equations can be simplified in several ways, all of which make them easier to solve.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Some of the simplifications allow some simple fluid dynamics problems to be solved in closed form.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In addition to the mass, momentum, and energy conservation equations, a thermodynamic equation of state that gives the pressure as a function of other thermodynamic variables is required to completely describe the problem.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] where p is pressure, ρ is density, and T is the absolute temperature, while Ru is the gas constant and M is molar mass for a particular gas.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] A constitutive relation may also be useful.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Three conservation laws are used to solve fluid dynamics problems, and may be written in integral or differential form.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The conservation laws may be applied to a region of the flow called a *control volume*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] A control volume is a discrete volume in space through which fluid is assumed to flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The integral formulations of the conservation laws are used to describe the change of mass, momentum, or energy within the control volume.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Differential formulations of the conservation laws apply Stokes' theorem to yield an expression that may be interpreted as the integral form of the law applied to an infinitesimally small volume (at a point) within the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The rate of change of fluid mass inside a control volume must be equal to the net rate of fluid flow into the volume.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Above, ρ is the fluid density, **u** is the flow velocity vector, and t is time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The left-hand side of the above expression is the rate of increase of mass within the volume and contains a triple integral over the control volume, whereas the right-hand side contains an integration over the surface of the control volume of mass convected into the system.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Mass flow into the system is accounted as positive, and since the normal vector to the surface is opposite to the sense of flow into the system the term is negated.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] applied to a control volume, is a statement that any change in momentum of the fluid within that control volume will be due to the net flow of momentum into the volume and the action of external forces acting on the fluid within the volume.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In the above integral formulation of this equation, the term on the left is the net change of momentum within the volume.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The first term on the right is the net rate at which momentum is convected into the volume.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The second term on the right is the force due to pressure on the volume's surfaces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The first two terms on the right are negated since momentum entering the system is accounted as positive, and the normal is opposite the direction of the velocity **u** and pressure forces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The third term on the right is the net acceleration of the mass within the volume due to any body forces (here represented by **f**body).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Surface forces, such as viscous forces, are represented by **F**surf, the net force due to shear forces acting on the volume surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The momentum balance can also be written for a *moving* control volume.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The following is the differential form of the momentum conservation equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Here, the volume is reduced to an infinitesimally small point, and both surface and body forces are accounted for in one total force, **F**.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] , which posits a linear relationship between the shear stress (due to internal friction forces) and the rate of strain of the fluid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The equation above is a vector equation in a three-dimensional flow, but it can be expressed as three scalar equations in three coordinate directions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The conservation of momentum equations for the compressible, viscous flow case is called the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The viscous dissipation function governs the rate at which the mechanical energy of the flow is converted to heat.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] requires that the dissipation term is always positive: viscosity cannot create energy within the control volume.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] All fluids are compressible to an extent; that is, changes in pressure or temperature cause changes in density.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] However, in many situations the changes in pressure and temperature are sufficiently small that the changes in density are negligible.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In this case the flow can be modelled as an incompressible flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Otherwise the more general compressible flow equations must be used.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Mathematically, incompressibility is expressed by saying that the density ρ of a fluid parcel does not change as it moves in the flow field, that is, ${\frac {\mathrm {D} \rho }{\mathrm {D} t}}=0\,,$ where ⁠D/D*t*⁠ is the material derivative, which is the sum of local and convective derivatives.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] This additional constraint simplifies the governing equations, especially in the case when the fluid has a uniform density.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] For flow of gases, to determine whether to use compressible or incompressible fluid dynamics, the Mach number of the flow is evaluated.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] As a rough guide, compressible effects can be ignored at Mach numbers below approximately 0.3.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] For liquids, whether the incompressible assumption is valid depends on the fluid properties (specifically the critical pressure and temperature of the fluid) and the flow conditions (how close to the critical pressure the actual flow pressure becomes).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Acoustic problems always require allowing compressibility, since sound waves are compression waves involving changes in pressure and density of the medium through which they propagate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] All fluids, except superfluids, are viscous, meaning that they exert some resistance to deformation: neighbouring parcels of fluid moving at different velocities exert viscous forces on each other.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The velocity gradient is referred to as a strain rate; it has dimensions *T*−1.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Isaac Newton showed that for many familiar fluids such as water and air, the stress due to these viscous forces is linearly related to the strain rate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Such fluids are called Newtonian fluids.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The coefficient of proportionality is called the fluid's viscosity; for Newtonian fluids, it is a fluid property that is independent of the strain rate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Non-Newtonian fluids have a more complicated, non-linear stress-strain behaviour.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The sub-discipline of rheology describes the stress-strain behaviours of such fluids, which include emulsions and slurries, some viscoelastic materials such as blood and some polymers, and *sticky liquids* such as latex, honey and lubricants.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The dynamic of fluid parcels is described with the help of Newton's second law.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] An accelerating parcel of fluid is subject to inertial effects.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The Reynolds number is a dimensionless quantity which characterises the magnitude of inertial effects compared to the magnitude of viscous effects.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] A low Reynolds number (*Re* ≪ 1) indicates that viscous forces are very strong compared to inertial forces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In such cases, inertial forces are sometimes neglected; this flow regime is called Stokes or creeping flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In contrast, high Reynolds numbers (*Re* ≫ 1) indicate that the inertial effects have more effect on the velocity field than the viscous (friction) effects.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In high Reynolds number flows, the flow is often modeled as an inviscid flow, an approximation in which viscosity is completely neglected.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Eliminating viscosity allows the Navier–Stokes equations to be simplified into the Euler equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The integration of the Euler equations along a streamline in an inviscid flow yields Bernoulli's equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] When, in addition to being inviscid, the flow is irrotational everywhere, Bernoulli's equation can completely describe the flow everywhere.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Such flows are called potential flows, because the velocity field may be expressed as the gradient of a potential energy expression.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] This idea can work fairly well when the Reynolds number is high.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] However, problems such as those involving solid boundaries may require that the viscosity be included.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Viscosity cannot be neglected near solid boundaries because the no-slip condition generates a thin region of large strain rate, the boundary layer, in which viscosity effects dominate and which thus generates vorticity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Therefore, to calculate net forces on bodies (such as wings), viscous flow equations must be used: inviscid flow theory fails to predict drag forces, a limitation known as the d'Alembert's paradox.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] A commonly used model, especially in computational fluid dynamics, is to use two flow models: the Euler equations away from the body, and boundary layer equations in a region close to the body.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The two solutions can then be matched with each other, using the method of matched asymptotic expansions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] A flow that is not a function of time is called **steady flow/laminar flow**.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Steady-state flow refers to the condition where the fluid properties at a point in the system do not change over time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Time dependent flow is known as unsteady (also called transient).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Whether a particular flow is steady or unsteady, can depend on the chosen frame of reference.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] For instance, laminar flow over a sphere is steady in the frame of reference that is stationary with respect to the sphere.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In a frame of reference that is stationary with respect to a background flow, the flow is unsteady.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Turbulent flows (or nonsteady or nonlaminar) are unsteady by definition.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] A turbulent flow can, however, be statistically stationary.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The random velocity field *U*(*x*, *t*) is statistically stationary if all statistics are invariant under a shift in time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] This roughly means that all statistical properties are constant in time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Often, the mean field is the object of interest, and this is constant too in a statistically stationary flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Steady flows are often more tractable than otherwise similar unsteady flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The governing equations of a steady problem have one dimension fewer (time) than the governing equations of the same problem without taking advantage of the steadiness of the flow field.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Turbulence is flow characterized by recirculation, eddies, and apparent randomness.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Flow in which turbulence is not exhibited is called laminar.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The presence of eddies or recirculation alone does not necessarily indicate turbulent flow—these phenomena may be present in laminar flow as well.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Mathematically, turbulent flow is often represented via a Reynolds decomposition, in which the flow is broken down into the sum of an average component and a perturbation component.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] It is believed that turbulent flows can be described well through the use of the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Direct numerical simulation (DNS), based on the Navier–Stokes equations, makes it possible to simulate turbulent flows at moderate Reynolds numbers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Restrictions depend on the power of the computer used and the efficiency of the solution algorithm.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The results of DNS have been found to agree well with experimental data for some flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Most flows of interest have Reynolds numbers much too high for DNS to be a viable option, given the state of computational power for the next few decades.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Any flight vehicle large enough to carry a human (L > 3 m), moving faster than 20 m/s (72 km/h; 45 mph) is well beyond the limit of DNS simulation (Re = 4 million).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Transport aircraft wings (such as on an Airbus A300 or Boeing 747) have Reynolds numbers of 40 million (based on the wing chord dimension).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Solving these real-life flow problems requires turbulence models for the foreseeable future.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations (RANS) combined with turbulence modelling provides a model of the effects of the turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Such a modelling mainly provides the additional momentum transfer by the Reynolds stresses, although the turbulence also enhances the heat and mass transfer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Another promising methodology is large eddy simulation (LES), especially in the form of detached eddy simulation (DES) — a combination of LES and RANS turbulence modelling.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] There are a large number of other possible approximations to fluid dynamic problems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Some of the more commonly used are listed below.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] While many flows (such as flow of water through a pipe) occur at low Mach numbers (subsonic flows), many flows of practical interest in aerodynamics or in turbomachines occur at high fractions of *M* = 1 (transonic flows) or in excess of it (supersonic or even hypersonic flows).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] New phenomena occur at these regimes such as instabilities in transonic flow, shock waves for supersonic flow, or non-equilibrium chemical behaviour due to ionization in hypersonic flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In practice, each of those flow regimes is treated separately.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Reactive flows are flows that are chemically reactive, which finds its applications in many areas, including combustion (IC engine), propulsion devices (rockets, jet engines, and so on), detonations, fire and safety hazards, and astrophysics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In addition to conservation of mass, momentum and energy, conservation of individual species (for example, mass fraction of methane in methane combustion) need to be derived, where the production/depletion rate of any species are obtained by simultaneously solving the equations of chemical kinetics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Magnetohydrodynamics is the multidisciplinary study of the flow of electrically conducting fluids in electromagnetic fields.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Examples of such fluids include plasmas, liquid metals, and salt water.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The fluid flow equations are solved simultaneously with Maxwell's equations of electromagnetism.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Relativistic fluid dynamics studies the macroscopic and microscopic fluid motion at large velocities comparable to the velocity of light.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] This branch of fluid dynamics accounts for the relativistic effects both from the special theory of relativity and the general theory of relativity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The governing equations are derived in Riemannian geometry for Minkowski spacetime.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] This branch of fluid dynamics augments the standard hydrodynamic equations with stochastic fluxes that model thermal fluctuations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] As formulated by Landau and Lifshitz, a white noise contribution obtained from the fluctuation-dissipation theorem of statistical mechanics is added to the viscous stress tensor and heat flux.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The concept of pressure is central to the study of both fluid statics and fluid dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] A pressure can be identified for every point in a body of fluid, regardless of whether the fluid is in motion or not.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Pressure can be measured using an aneroid, Bourdon tube, mercury column, or various other methods.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Some of the terminology that is necessary in the study of fluid dynamics is not found in other similar areas of study.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In particular, some of the terminology used in fluid dynamics is not used in fluid statics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The concepts of total pressure and dynamic pressure arise from Bernoulli's equation which is only valid when applied to frictionless flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Static pressure is identical to pressure and can be identified for every point in a fluid flow field.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] A point in a fluid flow where the flow has come to rest (that is to say, speed is equal to zero adjacent to some solid body immersed in the fluid flow) is of special significance.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] It is of such importance that it is given a special name—a stagnation point.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The static pressure at the stagnation point is of special significance and is given its own name—stagnation pressure.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Bernoulli’s equation is not valid in the boundary layer and the thin film of stationary fluid adjacent to a solid object is not regarded as a stagnation point.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Static pressure in the boundary layer is not related to stagnation pressure.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In the absence of shocks the stagnation pressure at a stagnation point is equal to the total pressure throughout the flow field.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] In a compressible fluid, it is convenient to define the total conditions (also called stagnation conditions) for all thermodynamic state properties (such as total temperature, total enthalpy, total speed of sound).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] These total flow conditions are a function of the fluid velocity and have different values in frames of reference with different motion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] To avoid potential ambiguity when referring to the properties of the fluid associated with the state of the fluid rather than its motion, the prefix "static" is commonly used (such as static temperature and static enthalpy).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Where there is no prefix, the fluid property is the static condition (so "density" and "static density" mean the same thing).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] The static conditions are independent of the frame of reference.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] Because the total flow conditions are defined by isentropically bringing the fluid to rest, there is no need to distinguish between total entropy and static entropy as they are always equal by definition.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/fluid-dynamics] As such, entropy is most commonly referred to as simply "entropy".
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] When a fluid is flowing through a closed channel such as a pipe or between two flat plates, either of two types of flow may occur depending on the velocity and viscosity of the fluid: laminar flow or turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Laminar flow occurs at lower velocities, below a threshold at which the flow becomes turbulent.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] The threshold velocity is determined by a dimensionless parameter characterizing the flow called the Reynolds number, which also depends on the viscosity and density of the fluid and dimensions of the channel.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Turbulent flow is a less orderly flow regime that is characterized by eddies or small packets of fluid particles, which result in lateral mixing.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] In non-scientific terms, laminar flow is *smooth*, while turbulent flow is *rough*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] The type of flow occurring in a fluid in a channel is important in fluid-dynamics problems and subsequently affects heat and mass transfer in fluid systems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] The dimensionless Reynolds number is an important parameter in the equations that describe whether fully developed flow conditions lead to laminar or turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] The Reynolds number is the ratio of the inertial force to the shearing force of the fluid: how fast the fluid is moving relative to how viscous it is, irrespective of the scale of the fluid system.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Laminar flow generally occurs when the fluid is moving slowly or the fluid is very viscous.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] If the Reynolds number is very small, much less than 1, then the fluid will exhibit Stokes, or creeping, flow, where the viscous forces of the fluid dominate the inertial forces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] The specific calculation of the Reynolds number, and the values where laminar flow occurs, will depend on the geometry of the flow system and flow pattern.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] For such systems, laminar flow occurs when the Reynolds number is below a critical value of approximately 2,040, though the transition range is typically between 1,800 and 2,100.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] For fluid systems occurring on external surfaces, such as flow past objects suspended in the fluid, other definitions for Reynolds numbers can be used to predict the type of flow around the object.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] The particle Reynolds number Rep would be used for particle suspended in flowing fluids, for example.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] As with flow in pipes, laminar flow typically occurs with lower Reynolds numbers, while turbulent flow and related phenomena, such as vortex shedding, occur with higher Reynolds numbers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] A common application of laminar flow is in the smooth flow of a viscous liquid through a tube or pipe.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] In that case, the velocity of flow varies from zero at the walls to a maximum along the cross-sectional centre of the vessel.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] The flow profile of laminar flow in a tube can be calculated by dividing the flow into thin cylindrical elements and applying the viscous force to them.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Another example is the flow of air over an aircraft wing.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] The boundary layer is a very thin sheet of air lying over the surface of the wing (and all other surfaces of the aircraft).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Because air has viscosity, this layer of air tends to adhere to the wing.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] As the wing moves forward through the air, the boundary layer at first flows smoothly over the streamlined shape of the airfoil.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Here, the flow is laminar and the boundary layer is a laminar layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Prandtl applied the concept of the laminar boundary layer to airfoils in 1904.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] An everyday example is the slow, smooth and optically transparent flow of shallow water over a smooth barrier.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Optical transparency is then reduced or lost entirely.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Laminar airflow is used to separate volumes of air, or prevent airborne contaminants from entering an area.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Laminar flow hoods are used to exclude contaminants from sensitive processes in science, electronics and medicine.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] Air curtains are frequently used in commercial settings to keep heated or refrigerated air from passing through doorways.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] A laminar flow reactor (LFR) is a reactor that uses laminar flow to study chemical reactions and process mechanisms.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] A laminar flow design for animal husbandry of rats for disease management was developed by Beall et al.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/laminar-flow] 1971 and became a standard around the world including in the then-Eastern Bloc.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The transition from laminar (left) to turbulent (right) flow of water from a tap occurs as the Reynolds number increases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In fluid dynamics, the **Reynolds number** (**Re**) is a dimensionless quantity that helps predict fluid flow patterns in different situations by measuring the ratio between inertial and viscous forces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] At low Reynolds numbers, flows tend to be dominated by laminar (sheet-like) flow, while at high Reynolds numbers, flows tend to be turbulent.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The turbulence results from differences in the fluid's speed and direction, which may sometimes intersect or even move counter to the overall direction of the flow (eddy currents).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] These eddy currents begin to churn the flow, using up energy in the process, which for liquids increases the chances of cavitation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number has wide applications, ranging from liquid flow in a pipe to the passage of air over an aircraft wing.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] It is used to predict the transition from laminar to turbulent flow and is used in the scaling of similar but different-sized flow situations, such as between an aircraft model in a wind tunnel and the full-size version.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The predictions of the onset of turbulence and the ability to calculate scaling effects can be used to help predict fluid behavior on a larger scale, such as in local or global air or water movement, and thereby the associated meteorological and climatological effects.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The concept was introduced by George Stokes in 1851, but the Reynolds number was named by Arnold Sommerfeld in 1908 after Osborne Reynolds who popularized its use in 1883 (an example of Stigler's law of eponymy).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number is the ratio of inertial forces to viscous forces within a fluid that is subjected to relative internal movement due to different fluid velocities.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] A region where these forces change behavior is known as a boundary layer, such as the bounding surface in the interior of a pipe.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] A similar effect is created by the introduction of a stream of high-velocity fluid into a low-velocity fluid, such as the hot gases emitted from a flame in air.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This relative movement generates fluid friction, which is a factor in developing turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Counteracting this effect is the viscosity of the fluid, which tends to inhibit turbulence.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number quantifies the relative importance of these two types of forces for given flow conditions and is a guide to when turbulent flow will occur in a particular situation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Such scaling is not linear and the application of Reynolds numbers to both situations allows scaling factors to be developed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] These are generally not independent numbers: liquids generally get less viscous as they become hotter, while gases generally become more viscous.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Both will generally become less dense as they become hotter, although the effect is substantially more pronounced in gases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For a (solid) object in a fluid, the characteristic length will vary with temperature - solids are typically even less temperature sensitive than liquids when it comes to density, but at sufficient flow speeds, the amount of frictional heat from traversing the fluid can be substantial.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number can be defined for several different situations where a fluid is in relative motion to a surface.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] These definitions generally include the fluid properties of density and viscosity, plus a velocity and a characteristic length or characteristic dimension (L in the above equation).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This dimension is a matter of convention—for example radius and diameter are equally valid to describe spheres or circles, but one is chosen by convention.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For aircraft or ships, the length or width can be used.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For flow in a pipe, or for a sphere moving in a fluid, the internal diameter is generally used today.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Other shapes such as rectangular pipes or non-spherical objects have an *equivalent diameter* defined.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For fluids of variable density such as compressible gases or fluids of variable viscosity such as non-Newtonian fluids, special rules apply.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The velocity may also be a matter of convention in some circumstances, notably stirred vessels.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In practice, matching the Reynolds number is not on its own sufficient to guarantee similitude.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Fluid flow is generally chaotic, and very small changes to shape and surface roughness of bounding surfaces can result in very different flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Nevertheless, Reynolds numbers are a very important guide and are widely used.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] If we know that the relevant physical quantities in a physical system are only $\rho ,u,L,\mu$ , then the Reynolds number is essentially fixed by the Buckingham π theorem.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Setting the three dimensions of $\rho ^{x_{1}}u^{x_{2}}L^{x_{3}}\mu ^{x_{4}}$ to zero, we obtain 3 independent linear constraints, so the solution space has 1 dimension, and it is spanned by the vector $(1,1,1,-1)$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Thus, any dimensionless quantity constructed out of $\rho ,u,L,\mu$ is a function of $\rho uL\mu ^{-1}$ , the Reynolds number.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This argument is written out in detail on the Scallop theorem page.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Each term in the above equation has the units of a "body force" (force per unit volume) with the same dimensions of a density multiplied by an acceleration.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Each term is thus dependent on the exact measurements of a flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] When we render the equation nondimensional, that is when we multiply it by a factor with inverse units of the base equation, we obtain a form that does not depend directly on the physical sizes.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This is why mathematically all Newtonian, incompressible flows with the same Reynolds number are comparable.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Notice also that in the above equation, the viscous terms vanish for Re → ∞.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Thus flows with high Reynolds numbers are approximately inviscid in the free stream.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Osborne Reynolds famously studied the conditions in which the flow of fluid in pipes transitioned from laminar flow to turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In his 1883 paper, Reynolds described the transition from laminar to turbulent flow in a classic experiment in which he examined the behaviour of water flow under different flow velocities using a small stream of dyed water introduced into the centre of clear water flow in a larger pipe.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The larger pipe was made of glass so the behaviour of the layer of the dyed stream could be observed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] At the end of this pipe, there was a flow control valve used to vary the water velocity inside the tube.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] When the velocity was low, the dyed layer remained distinct throughout the entire length of the large tube.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] When the velocity was increased, the layer broke up at a given point and diffused throughout the fluid's cross-section.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The point at which this happened was the transition point from laminar to turbulent flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] From these experiments came the dimensionless Reynolds number for dynamic similarity –the ratio of inertial forces to viscous forces.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Reynolds also proposed what is now known as the Reynolds averaging of turbulent flows, where quantities such as velocity are expressed as the sum of mean and fluctuating components.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Such averaging allows for 'bulk' description of turbulent flow, for example using the Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] where *A* is the cross-sectional area, and *P* is the wetted perimeter.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The wetted perimeter for a channel is the total perimeter of all channel walls that are in contact with the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This means that the length of the channel exposed to air is *not* included in the wetted perimeter.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For calculation involving flow in non-circular ducts, the hydraulic diameter can be substituted for the diameter of a circular duct, with reasonable accuracy, if the aspect ratio AR of the duct cross-section remains in the range ⁠1/4⁠ < AR < 4.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In boundary layer flow over a flat plate, experiments confirm that, after a certain length of flow, a laminar boundary layer will become unstable and turbulent.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This instability occurs across different scales and with different fluids, usually when Re*x* ≈ 5×105, where *x* is the distance from the leading edge of the flat plate, and the flow velocity is the freestream velocity of the fluid outside the boundary layer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For flow in a pipe of diameter *D*, experimental observations show that for "fully developed" flow, laminar flow occurs when Re*D* < 2300 and turbulent flow occurs when Re*D* > 2900.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] At the lower end of this range, a continuous turbulent-flow will form, but only at a very long distance from the inlet of the pipe.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The flow in between will begin to transition from laminar to turbulent and then back to laminar at irregular intervals, called intermittent flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This is due to the different speeds and conditions of the fluid in different areas of the pipe's cross-section, depending on other factors such as pipe roughness and flow uniformity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Laminar flow tends to dominate in the fast-moving center of the pipe while slower-moving turbulent flow dominates near the wall.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] As the Reynolds number increases, the continuous turbulent-flow moves closer to the inlet and the intermittency in between increases, until the flow becomes fully turbulent at Re*D* > 2900.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This result is generalized to non-circular channels using the hydraulic diameter, allowing a transition Reynolds number to be calculated for other shapes of channel.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] These transition Reynolds numbers are also called *critical Reynolds numbers*, and were studied by Osborne Reynolds around 1895.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The critical Reynolds number is different for every geometry.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For a fluid moving between two plane parallel surfaces—where the width is much greater than the space between the plates—then the characteristic dimension is equal to the distance between the plates.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This is consistent with the annular duct and rectangular duct cases above, taken to a limiting aspect ratio.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For calculating the flow of liquid with a free surface, the hydraulic radius must be determined.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This is the cross-sectional area of the channel divided by the wetted perimeter.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For a semi-circular channel, it is a quarter of the diameter (in case of full pipe flow).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For a rectangular channel, the hydraulic radius is the cross-sectional area divided by the wetted perimeter.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Reynolds numbers are used in airfoil design to (among other things) manage "scale effect" when computing/comparing characteristics (a tiny wing, scaled to be huge, will perform differently).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Fluid dynamicists define the *chord Reynolds number* *R* = *Vc*/*ν*, where *V* is the flight speed, *c* is the chord length, and *ν* is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid in which the airfoil operates, which is 1.460×10−5 m2/s for the atmosphere at sea level.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In some special studies a characteristic length other than chord may be used; rare is the "span Reynolds number", which is not to be confused with span-wise stations on a wing, where chord is still used.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number for an object moving in a fluid, called the particle Reynolds number and often denoted Rep, characterizes the nature of the surrounding flow and its fall velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Where the viscosity is naturally high, such as polymer solutions and polymer melts, flow is normally laminar.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number is very small and Stokes' law can be used to measure the viscosity of the fluid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Spheres are allowed to fall through the fluid and they reach the terminal velocity quickly, from which the viscosity can be determined.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The laminar flow of polymer solutions is exploited by animals such as fish and dolphins, who exude viscous solutions from their skin to aid flow over their bodies while swimming.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] It has been used in yacht racing by owners who want to gain a speed advantage by pumping a polymer solution such as low molecular weight polyoxyethylene in water, over the wetted surface of the hull.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] It is, however, a problem for mixing polymers, because turbulence is needed to distribute fine filler (for example) through the material.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Inventions such as the "cavity transfer mixer" have been developed to produce multiple folds into a moving melt so as to improve mixing efficiency.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The device can be fitted onto extruders to aid mixing.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For a sphere in a fluid, the characteristic length-scale is the diameter of the sphere and the characteristic velocity is that of the sphere relative to the fluid some distance away from the sphere, such that the motion of the sphere does not disturb that reference parcel of fluid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The density and viscosity are those belonging to the fluid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Note that purely laminar flow only exists up to Re = 10 under this definition.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Under the condition of low Re, the relationship between force and speed of motion is given by Stokes' law.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] At higher Reynolds numbers the drag on a sphere depends on surface roughness.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Thus, for example, adding dimples on the surface of a golf ball causes the boundary layer on the upstream side of the ball to transition from laminar to turbulent.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The turbulent boundary layer is able to remain attached to the surface of the ball much longer than a laminar boundary and so creates a narrower low-pressure wake and hence less pressure drag.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The reduction in pressure drag causes the ball to travel farther.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The equation for a rectangular object is identical to that of a sphere, with the object being approximated as an ellipsoid and the axis of length being chosen as the characteristic length scale.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Such considerations are important in natural streams, for example, where there are few perfectly spherical grains.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For grains in which measurement of each axis is impractical, sieve diameters are used instead as the characteristic particle length-scale.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Both approximations alter the values of the critical Reynolds number.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The particle Reynolds number is important in determining the terminal velocity of a particle.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] When the particle Reynolds number indicates laminar flow, Stokes' law can be used to calculate its fall velocity or settling velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] When the particle Reynolds number indicates turbulent flow, a turbulent drag law must be constructed to model the appropriate settling velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Laminar conditions apply up to Re = 10, fully turbulent from Re = 2000.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In a cylindrical vessel stirred by a central rotating paddle, turbine or propeller, the characteristic dimension is the diameter of the agitator *D*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The velocity *V* is *ND* where *N* is the rotational speed in rad per second.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The system is fully turbulent for values of Re above 10000.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Pressure drops seen for fully developed flow of fluids through pipes can be predicted using the Moody diagram which plots the Darcy–Weisbach friction factor *f* against Reynolds number Re and relative roughness ⁠*ε*/*D*⁠.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The diagram clearly shows the laminar, transition, and turbulent flow regimes as Reynolds number increases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The nature of pipe flow is strongly dependent on whether the flow is laminar or turbulent.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In order for two flows to be similar, they must have the same geometry and equal Reynolds and Euler numbers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] where $\mathrm {Re} _{\text{m}}$ is the Reynolds number for the model, and $\mathrm {Re}$ is full-scale Reynolds number, and similarly for the Euler numbers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] This allows engineers to perform experiments with reduced scale models in water channels or wind tunnels and correlate the data to the actual flows, saving on costs during experimentation and on lab time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Note that true dynamic similitude may require matching other dimensionless numbers as well, such as the Mach number used in compressible flows, or the Froude number that governs open-channel flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Some flows involve more dimensionless parameters than can be practically satisfied with the available apparatus and fluids, so one is forced to decide which parameters are most important.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For experimental flow modeling to be useful, it requires a fair amount of experience and judgment of the engineer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] An example where the mere Reynolds number is not sufficient for the similarity of flows (or even the flow regime – laminar or turbulent) are bounded flows, i.e. flows that are restricted by walls or other boundaries.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] A classical example of this is the Taylor–Couette flow, where the dimensionless ratio of radii of bounding cylinders is also important, and many technical applications where these distinctions play an important role.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Principles of these restrictions were developed by Maurice Marie Alfred Couette and Geoffrey Ingram Taylor and developed further by Floris Takens and David Ruelle.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In a turbulent flow, there is a range of scales of the time-varying fluid motion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The size of the largest scales of fluid motion (sometimes called eddies) are set by the overall geometry of the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] For instance, in an industrial smoke stack, the largest scales of fluid motion are as big as the diameter of the stack itself.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The size of the smallest scales is set by the Reynolds number.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] As the Reynolds number increases, smaller and smaller scales of the flow are visible.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In a smokestack, the smoke may appear to have many very small velocity perturbations or eddies, in addition to large bulky eddies.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In this sense, the Reynolds number is an indicator of the range of scales in the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The higher the Reynolds number, the greater the range of scales.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The largest eddies will always be the same size; the smallest eddies are determined by the Reynolds number.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] What is the explanation for this phenomenon?
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] A large Reynolds number indicates that viscous forces are not important at large scales of the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] With a strong predominance of inertial forces over viscous forces, the largest scales of fluid motion are undamped—there is not enough viscosity to dissipate their motions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The kinetic energy must "cascade" from these large scales to progressively smaller scales until a level is reached for which the scale is small enough for viscosity to become important (that is, viscous forces become of the order of inertial ones).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] It is at these small scales where the dissipation of energy by viscous action finally takes place.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number indicates at what scale this viscous dissipation occurs.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Poiseuille's law on blood circulation in the body is dependent on laminar flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In turbulent flow the flow rate is proportional to the square root of the pressure gradient, as opposed to its direct proportionality to pressure gradient in laminar flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Using the definition of the Reynolds number we can see that a large diameter with rapid flow, where the density of the blood is high, tends towards turbulence.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Rapid changes in vessel diameter may lead to turbulent flow, for instance when a narrower vessel widens to a larger one.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Furthermore, a bulge of atheroma may be the cause of turbulent flow, where audible turbulence may be detected with a stethoscope.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Reynolds number interpretation has been extended into the area of arbitrary complex systems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Such as financial flows, nonlinear networks, etc.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] In the latter case, an artificial viscosity is reduced to a nonlinear mechanism of energy distribution in complex network media.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Reynolds number then represents a basic control parameter that expresses a balance between injected and dissipated energy flows for an open boundary system.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] It has been shown that Reynolds critical regime separates two types of phase space motion: accelerator (attractor) and decelerator.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] High Reynolds number leads to a chaotic regime transition only in frame of strange attractor model.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] There are many dimensionless numbers in fluid mechanics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] The Reynolds number measures the ratio of advection and diffusion effects on structures in the velocity field, and is therefore closely related to Péclet numbers, which measure the ratio of these effects on other fields carried by the flow, for example, temperature and magnetic fields.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] Replacement of the kinematic viscosity *ν* = ⁠*μ*/*ρ*⁠ in Re by the thermal or magnetic diffusivity results in respectively the thermal Péclet number and the magnetic Reynolds number.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/reynolds-number] These are therefore related to Re by-products with ratios of diffusivities, namely the Prandtl number and magnetic Prandtl number.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In continuum mechanics, **viscosity** is a property of a fluid that quantifies the resistance force acting on fluids when there is relative motion between fluid parcels.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This resistance force is caused by the stress in fluid parcels, which ideally is directly proportional to the strain rate (the time derivative of strain) that arises when fluid parcels are in relative motion, and the relative speed between the boundary between adjacent fluid parcels is zero.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In liquids, viscosity arises from cohesive molecular forces, while in gases it results from molecular collisions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Except for the case of superfluidity, there is no fluid with zero viscosity, and thus all fluid flows involve viscous effects to some degree.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For liquids, it corresponds to the informal concept of *thickness*; for example, syrup has a higher viscosity than water.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Viscosity is defined scientifically as a force multiplied by a time divided by an area.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Thus its SI units are newton-seconds per metre squared, or pascal-seconds.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For instance, when a viscous fluid is forced through a tube, it flows more quickly near the tube's center line than near its walls.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Some stress (such as a pressure difference between the two ends of the tube) is needed to sustain the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This is because a force is required to overcome the friction between the layers of the fluid which are in relative motion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For a tube with a constant rate of flow, the strength of the compensating force is proportional to the fluid's viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In general, viscosity depends on a fluid's state, such as its temperature, pressure, and rate of deformation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, the dependence on some of these properties is negligible in certain cases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For example, the viscosity of a Newtonian fluid does not vary significantly with the rate of deformation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Zero viscosity (no resistance to shear stress) is observed only at very low temperatures in superfluids; otherwise, the second law of thermodynamics requires all fluids to have positive viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A fluid that has zero viscosity (non-viscous) is called *ideal* or *inviscid*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For non-Newtonian fluids' viscosity, there are pseudoplastic, plastic, and dilatant flows that are time-independent, and there are thixotropic and rheopectic flows that are time-dependent.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The word "viscosity" is derived from the Latin **viscum** ("mistletoe").
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] **Viscum** also referred to a viscous glue derived from mistletoe berries.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In materials science and engineering, there is often interest in understanding the forces or stresses involved in the deformation of a material.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For instance, if the material were a simple spring, the answer would be given by Hooke's law, which says that the force experienced by a spring is proportional to the distance displaced from equilibrium.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Stresses which can be attributed to the deformation of a material from some rest state are called elastic stresses.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In other materials, stresses are present which can be attributed to the deformation rate over time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For instance, in a fluid such as water the stresses which arise from shearing the fluid do not depend on the *distance* the fluid has been sheared; rather, they depend on how *quickly* the shearing occurs.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Viscosity is the material property which relates the viscous stresses in a material to the rate of change of a deformation (the strain rate).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Although it applies to general flows, it is easy to visualize and define in a simple shearing flow, such as a planar Couette flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In the Couette flow, a fluid is trapped between two infinitely large plates, one fixed and one in parallel motion at constant speed u (see illustration to the right).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] If the speed of the top plate is low enough (to avoid turbulence), then in steady state the fluid particles move parallel to it, and their speed varies from 0 at the bottom to u at the top.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Each layer of fluid moves faster than the one just below it, and friction between them gives rise to a force resisting their relative motion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In particular, the fluid applies on the top plate a force in the direction opposite to its motion, and an equal but opposite force on the bottom plate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] An external force is therefore required in order to keep the top plate moving at constant speed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In many fluids, the flow velocity is observed to vary linearly from zero at the bottom to u at the top.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The proportionality factor is the *dynamic viscosity* of the fluid, often simply referred to as the *viscosity*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] It is denoted by the Greek letter mu (μ).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] energy per unit volume multiplied by time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The aforementioned ratio $u/y$ is called the *rate of shear deformation* or *shear velocity*, and is the derivative of the fluid speed in the direction parallel to the normal vector of the plates (see illustrations to the right).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\tau =F/A$ , and $\partial u/\partial y$ is the local shear velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This expression is referred to as Newton's law of viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In shearing flows with planar symmetry, it is what *defines* $\mu$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] It is a special case of the general definition of viscosity (see below), which can be expressed in coordinate-free form.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Use of the Greek letter mu ( $\mu$ ) for the dynamic viscosity (sometimes also called the *absolute viscosity*) is common among mechanical and chemical engineers, as well as mathematicians and physicists.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, the Greek letter eta ( $\eta$ ) is also used by chemists, physicists, and the IUPAC.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The viscosity $\mu$ is sometimes also called the *shear viscosity*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, at least one author discourages the use of this terminology, noting that $\mu$ can appear in non-shearing flows in addition to shearing flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In fluid dynamics, it is sometimes more appropriate to work in terms of *kinematic viscosity* (sometimes also called the *momentum diffusivity*), defined as the ratio of the dynamic viscosity (μ) over the density of the fluid (ρ).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] energy per unit mass multiplied by time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In very general terms, the viscous stresses in a fluid are defined as those resulting from the relative velocity of different fluid particles.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] As such, the viscous stresses must depend on spatial gradients of the flow velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] If the velocity gradients are small, then to a first approximation the viscous stresses depend only on the first derivatives of the velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\mu _{ijk\ell }$ is a viscosity tensor that maps the velocity gradient tensor $\partial v_{k}/\partial r_{\ell }$ onto the viscous stress tensor $\tau _{ij}$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Since the indices in this expression can vary from 1 to 3, there are 81 "viscosity coefficients" $\mu _{ijkl}$ in total.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] and furthermore, it is assumed that no viscous forces may arise when the fluid is undergoing simple rigid-body rotation, thus $\beta =\gamma$ , leaving only two independent parameters.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The most usual decomposition is in terms of the standard (scalar) viscosity $\mu$ and the bulk viscosity $\kappa$ such that $\alpha =\kappa -{\tfrac {2}{3}}\mu$ and $\beta =\gamma =\mu$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\mathbf {\delta }$ is the unit tensor.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This equation can be thought of as a generalized form of Newton's law of viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The bulk viscosity (also called volume viscosity) expresses a type of internal friction that resists the shearless compression or expansion of a fluid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Knowledge of $\kappa$ is frequently not necessary in fluid dynamics problems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For example, an incompressible fluid satisfies $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {v} =0$ and so the term containing $\kappa$ drops out.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Moreover, $\kappa$ is often assumed to be negligible for gases since it is 0 in a monatomic ideal gas.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] One situation in which $\kappa$ can be important is the calculation of energy loss in sound and shock waves, described by Stokes' law of sound attenuation, since these phenomena involve rapid expansions and compressions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The defining equations for viscosity are not fundamental laws of nature, so their usefulness, as well as methods for measuring or calculating the viscosity, must be established using separate means.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A potential issue is that viscosity depends, in principle, on the full microscopic state of the fluid, which encompasses the positions and momenta of every particle in the system.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Such highly detailed information is typically not available in realistic systems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, under certain conditions most of this information can be shown to be negligible.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In particular, for Newtonian fluids near equilibrium and far from boundaries (bulk state), the viscosity depends only space- and time-dependent macroscopic fields (such as temperature and density) defining local equilibrium.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Nevertheless, viscosity may still carry a non-negligible dependence on several system properties, such as temperature, pressure, and the amplitude and frequency of any external forcing.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Therefore, precision measurements of viscosity are only defined with respect to a specific fluid state.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] To standardize comparisons among experiments and theoretical models, viscosity data is sometimes extrapolated to ideal limiting cases, such as the *zero shear* limit, or (for gases) the *zero density* limit.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This perspective is implicit in Newton's law of viscosity, $\tau =\mu (\partial u/\partial y)$ , because the shear stress $\tau$ has units equivalent to a momentum flux, i.e., momentum per unit time per unit area.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Thus, $\tau$ can be interpreted as specifying the flow of momentum in the y direction from one fluid layer to the next.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Per Newton's law of viscosity, this momentum flow occurs across a velocity gradient, and the magnitude of the corresponding momentum flux is determined by the viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The analogy with heat and mass transfer can be made explicit.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Just as heat flows from high temperature to low temperature and mass flows from high density to low density, momentum flows from high velocity to low velocity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\rho$ is the density, $\mathbf {J}$ and $\mathbf {q}$ are the mass and heat fluxes, and D and $k_{t}$ are the mass diffusivity and thermal conductivity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The fact that mass, momentum, and energy (heat) transport are among the most relevant processes in continuum mechanics is not a coincidence: these are among the few physical quantities that are conserved at the microscopic level in interparticle collisions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Thus, rather than being dictated by the fast and complex microscopic interaction timescale, their dynamics occurs on macroscopic timescales, as described by the various equations of transport theory and hydrodynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Newton's law of viscosity is not a fundamental law of nature, but rather a constitutive equation (like Hooke's law, Fick's law, and Ohm's law) which serves to define the viscosity $\mu$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Its form is motivated by experiments which show that for a wide range of fluids, $\mu$ is independent of strain rate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Gases, water, and many common liquids can be considered Newtonian in ordinary conditions and contexts.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, there are many non-Newtonian fluids that significantly deviate from this behavior.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Trouton's ratio is the ratio of extensional viscosity to shear viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For a Newtonian fluid, the Trouton ratio is 3.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Shear-thinning liquids are very commonly, but misleadingly, described as thixotropic.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Viscosity may also depend on the fluid's physical state (temperature and pressure) and other, *external*, factors.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For gases and other compressible fluids, it depends on temperature and varies very slowly with pressure.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The viscosity of some fluids may depend on other factors.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A magnetorheological fluid, for example, becomes thicker when subjected to a magnetic field, possibly to the point of behaving like a solid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The viscous forces that arise during fluid flow are distinct from the elastic forces that occur in a solid in response to shear, compression, or extension stresses.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] While in the latter the stress is proportional to the *amount* of shear deformation, in a fluid it is proportional to the *rate* of deformation over time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For this reason, James Clerk Maxwell used the term *fugitive elasticity* for fluid viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, many liquids (including water) will briefly react like elastic solids when subjected to sudden stress.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Conversely, many "solids" (even granite) will flow like liquids, albeit very slowly, even under arbitrarily small stress.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Such materials are best described as viscoelastic—that is, possessing both elasticity (reaction to deformation) and viscosity (reaction to rate of deformation).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Viscoelastic solids may exhibit both shear viscosity and bulk viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The extensional viscosity is a linear combination of the shear and bulk viscosities that describes the reaction of a solid elastic material to elongation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] It is widely used for characterizing polymers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In geology, earth materials that exhibit viscous deformation at least three orders of magnitude greater than their elastic deformation are sometimes called rheids.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Viscosity is measured with various types of viscometers and rheometers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Close temperature control of the fluid is essential to obtain accurate measurements, particularly in materials like lubricants, whose viscosity can double with a change of only 5 °C.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A rheometer is used for fluids that cannot be defined by a single value of viscosity and therefore require more parameters to be set and measured than is the case for a viscometer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For some fluids, the viscosity is constant over a wide range of shear rates (Newtonian fluids).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The fluids without a constant viscosity (non-Newtonian fluids) cannot be described by a single number.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Non-Newtonian fluids exhibit a variety of different correlations between shear stress and shear rate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] One of the most common instruments for measuring kinematic viscosity is the glass capillary viscometer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In coating industries, viscosity may be measured with a cup in which the efflux time is measured.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] There are several sorts of cup—such as the Zahn cup and the Ford viscosity cup—with the usage of each type varying mainly according to the industry.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Also used in coatings, a *Stormer viscometer* employs load-based rotation to determine viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The viscosity is reported in Krebs units (KU), which are unique to Stormer viscometers.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Vibrating viscometers can also be used to measure viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Resonant, or vibrational viscometers work by creating shear waves within the liquid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In this method, the sensor is submerged in the fluid and is made to resonate at a specific frequency.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] As the surface of the sensor shears through the liquid, energy is lost due to its viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This dissipated energy is then measured and converted into a viscosity reading.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A higher viscosity causes a greater loss of energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Volume viscosity can be measured with an acoustic rheometer.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Apparent viscosity is a calculation derived from tests performed on drilling fluid used in oil or gas well development.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] These calculations and tests help engineers develop and maintain the properties of the drilling fluid to the specifications required.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Nanoviscosity (viscosity sensed by nanoprobes) can be measured by fluorescence correlation spectroscopy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The SI unit of dynamic viscosity is the newton-second per metre squared (N·s/m2), also frequently expressed in the equivalent forms pascal-second (Pa·s), kilogram per meter per second (kg·m−1·s−1) and poiseuille (Pl).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The CGS unit is the poise (P, or g·cm−1·s−1 = 0.1 Pa·s), named after Jean Léonard Marie Poiseuille.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] It is commonly expressed, particularly in ASTM standards, as *centipoise* (cP).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The centipoise is convenient because the viscosity of water at 20 °C is about 1 cP, and one centipoise is equal to the SI millipascal second (mPa·s).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The SI unit of kinematic viscosity is metre squared per second (m2/s), whereas the CGS unit for kinematic viscosity is the **stokes** (St, or cm2·s−1 = 0.0001 m2·s−1), named after Sir George Gabriel Stokes.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In U.S. usage, *stoke* is sometimes used as the singular form.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The submultiple *centistokes* (cSt) is often used instead, 1 cSt = 1 mm2·s−1 = 10−6 m2·s−1.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] 1 cSt is 1 cP divided by 1000 kg/m^3, close to the density of water.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The kinematic viscosity of water at 20 °C is about 1 cSt.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The most frequently used systems of US customary, or Imperial, units are the British Gravitational (BG) and English Engineering (EE).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In the BG system, dynamic viscosity has units of *pound*-seconds per square foot (lb·s/ft2), and in the EE system it has units of *pound-force*-seconds per square foot (lbf·s/ft2).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The pound and pound-force are equivalent; the two systems differ only in how force and mass are defined.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Kinematic viscosity has units of square feet per second (ft2/s) in both the BG and EE systems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Nonstandard units include the reyn (lbf·s/in2), a British unit of dynamic viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In the automotive industry the viscosity index is used to describe the change of viscosity with temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The reciprocal of viscosity is *fluidity*, usually symbolized by $\phi =1/\mu$ or $F=1/\mu$ , depending on the convention used, measured in *reciprocal poise* (P−1, or cm·s·g−1), sometimes called the *rhe*.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Fluidity is seldom used in engineering practice.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] At one time the petroleum industry relied on measuring kinematic viscosity by means of the Saybolt viscometer, and expressing kinematic viscosity in units of Saybolt universal seconds (SUS).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Other abbreviations such as SSU (*Saybolt seconds universal*) or SUV (*Saybolt universal viscosity*) are sometimes used.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Kinematic viscosity in centistokes can be converted from SUS according to the arithmetic and the reference table provided in ASTM D 2161.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Momentum transport in gases is mediated by discrete molecular collisions, and in liquids by attractive forces that bind molecules close together.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Because of this, the dynamic viscosities of liquids are typically much larger than those of gases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In addition, viscosity tends to increase with temperature in gases and decrease with temperature in liquids.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Above the liquid-gas critical point, the liquid and gas phases are replaced by a single supercritical phase.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In this regime, the mechanisms of momentum transport interpolate between liquid-like and gas-like behavior.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For example, along a supercritical isobar (constant-pressure surface), the kinematic viscosity decreases at low temperature and increases at high temperature, with a minimum in between.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\hbar$ is the Planck constant, $m_{\text{e}}$ is the electron mass, and m is the molecular mass.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In general, however, the viscosity of a system depends in detail on how the molecules constituting the system interact, and there are no simple but correct formulas for it.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The simplest exact expressions are the Green–Kubo relations for the linear shear viscosity or the *transient time correlation function* expressions derived by Evans and Morriss in 1988.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Although these expressions are each exact, calculating the viscosity of a dense fluid using these relations currently requires the use of molecular dynamics computer simulations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Somewhat more progress can be made for a dilute gas, as elementary assumptions about how gas molecules move and interact lead to a basic understanding of the molecular origins of viscosity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] More sophisticated treatments can be constructed by systematically coarse-graining the equations of motion of the gas molecules.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] An example of such a treatment is Chapman–Enskog theory, which derives expressions for the viscosity of a dilute gas from the Boltzmann equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Consider a dilute gas moving parallel to the x -axis with velocity $u(y)$ that depends only on the y coordinate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] To simplify the discussion, the gas is assumed to have uniform temperature and density.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Under these assumptions, the x velocity of a molecule passing through $y=0$ is equal to whatever velocity that molecule had when its mean free path $\lambda$ began.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\alpha$ is a numerical constant on the order of 1 .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Viscosity in gases arises principally from the molecular diffusion that transports momentum between layers of flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $k_{\text{B}}$ is the Boltzmann constant, m the molecular mass, and $\alpha$ a numerical constant on the order of 1 .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The quantity $\lambda$ , the mean free path, measures the average distance a molecule travels between collisions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Even without *a priori* knowledge of $\alpha$ , this expression has nontrivial implications.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In particular, since $\lambda$ is typically inversely proportional to density and increases with temperature, $\mu$ itself should increase with temperature and be independent of density at fixed temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In fact, both of these predictions persist in more sophisticated treatments, and accurately describe experimental observations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] By contrast, liquid viscosity typically decreases with temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In this case $\lambda$ is independent of temperature, so $\mu \propto T^{1/2}$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For more complicated molecular models, however, $\lambda$ depends on temperature in a non-trivial way, and simple kinetic arguments as used here are inadequate.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] More fundamentally, the notion of a mean free path becomes imprecise for particles that interact over a finite range, which limits the usefulness of the concept for describing real-world gases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A technique developed by Sydney Chapman and David Enskog in the early 1900s allows a more refined calculation of $\mu$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] It is based on the Boltzmann equation, which provides a statistical description of a dilute gas in terms of intermolecular interactions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The technique allows accurate calculation of $\mu$ for molecular models that are more realistic than rigid elastic spheres, such as those incorporating intermolecular attractions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Doing so is necessary to reproduce the correct temperature dependence of $\mu$ , which experiments show increases more rapidly than the $T^{1/2}$ trend predicted for rigid elastic spheres.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Indeed, the Chapman–Enskog analysis shows that the predicted temperature dependence can be tuned by varying the parameters in various molecular models.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A simple example is the Sutherland model, which describes rigid elastic spheres with *weak* mutual attraction.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This expression is usually named Sutherland's formula.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] If $\mu$ is known from experiments at $T=T_{0}$ and at least one other temperature, then S can be calculated.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Expressions for $\mu$ obtained in this way are qualitatively accurate for a number of simple gases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Slightly more sophisticated models, such as the Lennard-Jones potential, or the more flexible Mie potential, may provide better agreement with experiments, but only at the cost of a more opaque dependence on temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A further advantage of these more complex interaction potentials is that they can be used to develop accurate models for a wide variety of properties using the same potential parameters.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In situations where little experimental data is available, this makes it possible to obtain model parameters from fitting to properties such as pure-fluid vapour-liquid equilibria, before using the parameters thus obtained to predict the viscosities of interest with reasonable accuracy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In some systems, the assumption of spherical symmetry must be abandoned, as is the case for vapors with highly polar molecules like H2O.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In these cases, the Chapman–Enskog analysis is significantly more complicated.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In the kinetic-molecular picture, a non-zero bulk viscosity arises in gases whenever there are non-negligible relaxational timescales governing the exchange of energy between the translational energy of molecules and their internal energy, e.g. rotational and vibrational.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] As such, the bulk viscosity is 0 for a monatomic ideal gas, in which the internal energy of molecules is negligible, but is nonzero for a gas like carbon dioxide, whose molecules possess both rotational and vibrational energy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In contrast with gases, there is no simple yet accurate picture for the molecular origins of viscosity in liquids.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] At the simplest level of description, the relative motion of adjacent layers in a liquid is opposed primarily by attractive molecular forces acting across the layer boundary.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In this picture, one (correctly) expects viscosity to decrease with increasing temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This is because increasing temperature increases the random thermal motion of the molecules, which makes it easier for them to overcome their attractive interactions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Building on this visualization, a simple theory can be constructed in analogy with the discrete structure of a solid: groups of molecules in a liquid are visualized as forming "cages" which surround and enclose single molecules.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] These cages can be occupied or unoccupied, and stronger molecular attraction corresponds to stronger cages.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Due to random thermal motion, a molecule "hops" between cages at a rate which varies inversely with the strength of molecular attractions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In equilibrium these "hops" are not biased in any direction.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] On the other hand, in order for two adjacent layers to move relative to each other, the "hops" must be biased in the direction of the relative motion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $N_{\text{A}}$ is the Avogadro constant, h is the Planck constant, V is the volume of a mole of liquid, and $T_{\text{b}}$ is the normal boiling point.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where A and B are constants fit from data.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] On the other hand, several authors express caution with respect to this model.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Errors as large as 30% can be encountered using equation (**1**), compared with fitting equation (**2**) to experimental data.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] More fundamentally, the physical assumptions underlying equation (**1**) have been criticized.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] It has also been argued that the exponential dependence in equation (**1**) does not necessarily describe experimental observations more accurately than simpler, non-exponential expressions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In light of these shortcomings, the development of a less ad hoc model is a matter of practical interest.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Foregoing simplicity in favor of precision, it is possible to write rigorous expressions for viscosity starting from the fundamental equations of motion for molecules.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A classic example of this approach is Irving–Kirkwood theory.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] On the other hand, such expressions are given as averages over multiparticle correlation functions and are therefore difficult to apply in practice.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In general, empirically derived expressions (based on existing viscosity measurements) appear to be the only consistently reliable means of calculating viscosity in liquids.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] At the same time equilibrium liquids follow the Arrhenius equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The same molecular-kinetic picture of a single component gas can also be applied to a gaseous mixture.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For instance, in the Chapman–Enskog approach the viscosity $\mu _{\text{mix}}$ of a binary mixture of gases can be written in terms of the individual component viscosities $\mu _{1,2}$ , their respective volume fractions, and the intermolecular interactions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] As for the single-component gas, the dependence of $\mu _{\text{mix}}$ on the parameters of the intermolecular interactions enters through various collisional integrals which may not be expressible in closed form.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] To obtain usable expressions for $\mu _{\text{mix}}$ which reasonably match experimental data, the collisional integrals may be computed numerically or from correlations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In some cases, the collision integrals are regarded as fitting parameters, and are fitted directly to experimental data.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This is a common approach in the development of reference equations for gas-phase viscosities.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] An example of such a procedure is the Sutherland approach for the single-component gas, discussed above.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For gas mixtures consisting of simple molecules, Revised Enskog Theory has been shown to accurately represent both the density- and temperature dependence of the viscosity over a wide range of conditions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] As for pure liquids, the viscosity of a blend of liquids is difficult to predict from molecular principles.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] One method is to extend the molecular "cage" theory presented above for a pure liquid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This can be done with varying levels of sophistication.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\alpha$ is an empirical parameter, and $x_{1,2}$ and $\mu _{1,2}$ are the respective mole fractions and viscosities of the component liquids.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Since blending is an important process in the lubricating and oil industries, a variety of empirical and proprietary equations exist for predicting the viscosity of a blend.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Depending on the solute and range of concentration, an aqueous electrolyte solution can have either a larger or smaller viscosity compared with pure water at the same temperature and pressure.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For instance, a 20% saline (sodium chloride) solution has viscosity over 1.5 times that of pure water, whereas a 20% potassium iodide solution has viscosity about 0.91 times that of pure water.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\mu _{0}$ is the viscosity of the solvent, c is the concentration, and A is a positive constant which depends on both solvent and solute properties.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, this expression is only valid for very dilute solutions, having c less than 0.1 mol/L.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In particular, a negative value of B is able to account for the decrease in viscosity observed in some solutions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Estimated values of these constants are shown below for sodium chloride and potassium iodide at temperature 25 °C (mol = mole, L = liter).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Such suspensions generally exhibit non-Newtonian behavior.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, for dilute systems in steady flows, the behavior is Newtonian and expressions for $\mu _{\text{eff}}$ can be derived directly from the particle dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In a very dilute system, with volume fraction $\phi \lesssim 0.02$ , interactions between the suspended particles can be ignored.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In such a case one can explicitly calculate the flow field around each particle independently, and combine the results to obtain $\mu _{\text{eff}}$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where $\mu _{0}$ is the viscosity of the suspending liquid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The linear dependence on $\phi$ is a consequence of neglecting interparticle interactions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where the coefficient B may depend on the particle shape (e.g. spheres, rods, disks).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Experimental determination of the precise value of B is difficult, however: even the prediction $B=5/2$ for spheres has not been conclusively validated, with various experiments finding values in the range $1.5\lesssim B\lesssim 5$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This deficiency has been attributed to difficulty in controlling experimental conditions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In denser suspensions, $\mu _{\text{eff}}$ acquires a nonlinear dependence on $\phi$ , which indicates the importance of interparticle interactions.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Various analytical and semi-empirical schemes exist for capturing this regime.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] and the coefficient $B_{1}$ is fit from experimental data or approximated from the microscopic theory.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] However, some authors advise caution in applying such simple formulas since non-Newtonian behavior appears in dense suspensions ( $\phi \gtrsim 0.25$ for spheres), or in suspensions of elongated or flexible particles.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] There is a distinction between a suspension of solid particles, described above, and an emulsion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The latter is a suspension of tiny droplets, which themselves may exhibit internal circulation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The presence of internal circulation can decrease the observed effective viscosity, and different theoretical or semi-empirical models must be used.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where Q is a relevant activation energy, given in terms of molecular parameters; T is temperature; R is the molar gas constant; and A is approximately a constant.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The activation energy Q takes a different value depending on whether the high or low temperature limit is being considered: it changes from a high value *Q*H at low temperatures (in the glassy state) to a low value *Q*L at high temperatures (in the liquid state).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For intermediate temperatures, Q varies nontrivially with temperature and the simple Arrhenius form fails.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] where A , B , C , D are all constants, provides a good fit to experimental data over the entire range of temperatures, while at the same time reducing to the correct Arrhenius form in the low and high temperature limits.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This expression, also known as Duouglas-Doremus-Ojovan model, can be motivated from various theoretical models of amorphous materials at the atomic level.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] A two-exponential equation for the viscosity can be derived within the Dyre shoving model of supercooled liquids, where the Arrhenius energy barrier is identified with the high-frequency shear modulus times a characteristic shoving volume.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Finally, $k_{B}$ denotes the Boltzmann constant.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] In contrast to the viscosity of the fluid itself, which must be positive by the second law of thermodynamics, the eddy viscosity can be negative.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Because viscosity depends continuously on temperature and pressure, it cannot be fully characterized by a finite number of experimental measurements.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Predictive formulas become necessary if experimental values are not available at the temperatures and pressures of interest.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] This capability is important for thermophysical simulations, in which the temperature and pressure of a fluid can vary continuously with space and time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For the simplest fluids, such as dilute monatomic gases and their mixtures, *ab initio* quantum mechanical computations can accurately predict viscosity in terms of fundamental atomic constants, i.e., without reference to existing viscosity measurements.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For the special case of dilute helium, uncertainties in the *ab initio* calculated viscosity are two order of magnitudes smaller than uncertainties in experimental values.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For slightly more complex fluids and mixtures at moderate densities (i.e. sub-critical densities) Revised Enskog Theory can be used to predict viscosities with some accuracy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Revised Enskog Theory is predictive in the sense that predictions for viscosity can be obtained using parameters fitted to other, pure-fluid thermodynamic properties or transport properties, thus requiring no *a priori* experimental viscosity measurements.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] For most fluids, high-accuracy, first-principles computations are not feasible.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Rather, theoretical or empirical expressions must be fit to existing viscosity measurements.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] If such an expression is fit to high-fidelity data over a large range of temperatures and pressures, then it is called a "reference correlation" for that fluid.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Reference correlations have been published for many pure fluids; a few examples are water, carbon dioxide, ammonia, benzene, and xenon.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Many of these cover temperature and pressure ranges that encompass gas, liquid, and supercritical phases.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Thermophysical modeling software often relies on reference correlations for predicting viscosity at user-specified temperature and pressure.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Examples are REFPROP (proprietary) and CoolProp (open-source).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] Viscosity can also be computed using formulas that express it in terms of the statistics of individual particle trajectories.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] These formulas include the Green–Kubo relations for the linear shear viscosity and the *transient time correlation function* expressions derived by Evans and Morriss in 1988.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The advantage of these expressions is that they are formally exact and valid for general systems.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] The disadvantage is that they require detailed knowledge of particle trajectories, available only in computationally expensive simulations such as molecular dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p01] An accurate model for interparticle interactions is also required, which may be difficult to obtain for complex molecules.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] Observed values of viscosity vary over several orders of magnitude, even for common substances (see the order of magnitude table below).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] For instance, a 70% sucrose (sugar) solution has a viscosity over 400 times that of water, and 26,000 times that of air.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] More dramatically, pitch has been estimated to have a viscosity 230 billion times that of water.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] The dynamic viscosity $\mu$ of water is about 0.89 mPa·s at room temperature (25 °C).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] As a function of temperature in kelvins, the viscosity can be estimated using the semi-empirical Vogel-Fulcher-Tammann equation: $\mu =Ae^{\frac {B}{T-C}}$ where *A* = 0.02939 mPa·s, *B* = 507.88 K, and *C* = 149.3 K.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] Experimentally determined values of the viscosity are also given in the table below.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] The values at 20 °C are a useful reference: there, the dynamic viscosity is about 1 cP and the kinematic viscosity is about 1 cSt.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] Under standard atmospheric conditions (25 °C and pressure of 1 bar), the dynamic viscosity of air is 18.5 μPa·s, roughly 50 times smaller than the viscosity of water at the same temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] Except at very high pressure, the viscosity of air depends mostly on the temperature.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] which is accurate in the range −20 °C to 400 °C.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] For this formula to be valid, the temperature must be given in kelvins; $\eta _{\text{air}}$ then corresponds to the viscosity in Pa·s.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] The following table illustrates the range of viscosity values observed in common substances.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] Unless otherwise noted, a temperature of 25 °C and a pressure of 1 atmosphere are assumed.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/viscosity-p02] The values listed are representative estimates only, as they do not account for measurement uncertainties, variability in material definitions, or non-Newtonian behavior.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In continuum mechanics, **vorticity** is a pseudovector (or axial vector) field that describes the local spinning motion of a continuum near some point (the tendency of something to rotate), as would be seen by an observer located at that point and traveling along with the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] It is an important quantity in the dynamical theory of fluids and provides a convenient framework for understanding a variety of complex flow phenomena, such as the generation of lift on wings.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Conceptually, ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ could be determined by marking parts of a continuum in a small neighborhood of the point in question, and watching their *relative* displacements as they move along the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The vorticity ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ would be twice the mean angular velocity vector of those particles relative to their center of mass, oriented according to the right-hand rule.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In a two-dimensional flow, ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ is always perpendicular to the plane of the flow, and can therefore be considered a scalar field.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The dynamics of vorticity are fundamentally linked to drag through the Josephson-Anderson relation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Mathematically, the vorticity of a three-dimensional flow is a pseudovector field, usually denoted by ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ , defined as the curl of the velocity field $\mathbf {v}$ describing the continuum motion.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] We may also express this in index notation as $\omega _{i}=\varepsilon _{ijk}{\frac {\partial v_{k}}{\partial x_{j}}}$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In words, the vorticity tells how the velocity vector changes when one moves by an infinitesimal distance in a direction perpendicular to it.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The vorticity is also related to the flow's circulation (line integral of the velocity) along a closed path by the (classical) Stokes' theorem.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Namely, for any infinitesimal surface element *C* with normal direction $\mathbf {n}$ and area $dA$ , the circulation $d\Gamma$ along the perimeter of C is the dot product ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}\cdot (\mathbf {n} \,dA)$ where ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ is the vorticity at the center of C .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Since vorticity is an axial vector, it can be associated with a second-order antisymmetric tensor ${\boldsymbol {\Omega }}$ (the so-called vorticity or rotation tensor), which is said to be the dual of ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] where $\varepsilon _{ijk}$ is the three-dimensional Levi-Civita tensor.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In a mass of continuum that is rotating like a rigid body, the vorticity is twice the angular velocity vector of that rotation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] This is the case, for example, in the central core of a Rankine vortex.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The vorticity may be nonzero even when all particles are flowing along straight and parallel pathlines, if there is shear (that is, if the flow speed varies across streamlines).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] For example, in the laminar flow within a pipe with constant cross section, all particles travel parallel to the axis of the pipe; but faster near that axis, and practically stationary next to the walls.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The vorticity will be zero on the axis, and maximum near the walls, where the shear is largest.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Conversely, a flow may have zero vorticity even though its particles travel along curved trajectories.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] An example is the ideal irrotational vortex, where most particles rotate about some straight axis, with speed inversely proportional to their distances to that axis.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] A small parcel of continuum that does not straddle the axis will be rotated in one sense but sheared in the opposite sense, in such a way that their mean angular velocity *about their center of mass* is zero.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Another way to visualize vorticity is to imagine that, instantaneously, a tiny part of the continuum becomes solid and the rest of the flow disappears.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] If that tiny new solid particle is rotating, rather than just moving with the flow, then there is vorticity in the flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In the figure below, the left subfigure demonstrates no vorticity, and the right subfigure demonstrates existence of vorticity.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The evolution of the vorticity field in time is described by the vorticity equation, which can be derived from the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In many real flows where the viscosity can be neglected (more precisely, in flows with high Reynolds number), the vorticity field can be modeled by a collection of discrete vortices, the vorticity being negligible everywhere except in small regions of space surrounding the axes of the vortices.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] This is true in the case of two-dimensional potential flow (i.e. two-dimensional zero viscosity flow), in which case the flowfield can be modeled as a complex-valued field on the complex plane.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Vorticity is useful for understanding how ideal potential flow solutions can be perturbed to model real flows.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In general, the presence of viscosity causes a diffusion of vorticity away from the vortex cores into the general flow field; this flow is accounted for by a diffusion term in the vorticity transport equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] A **vortex line** or **vorticity line** is a line which is everywhere tangent to the local vorticity vector.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] where ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}=(\omega _{x},\omega _{y},\omega _{z})$ is the vorticity vector in Cartesian coordinates.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] A **vortex tube** is the surface in the continuum formed by all vortex lines passing through a given (reducible) closed curve in the continuum.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The 'strength' of a vortex tube (also called **vortex flux**) is the integral of the vorticity across a cross-section of the tube, and is the same everywhere along the tube (because vorticity has zero divergence).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] It is a consequence of Helmholtz's theorems (or equivalently, of Kelvin's circulation theorem) that in an inviscid fluid the 'strength' of the vortex tube is also constant with time.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Viscous effects introduce frictional losses and time dependence.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In a three-dimensional flow, vorticity (as measured by the volume integral of the square of its magnitude) can be intensified when a vortex line is extended — a phenomenon known as vortex stretching.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] This phenomenon occurs in the formation of a bathtub vortex in outflowing water, and the build-up of a tornado by rising air currents.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] A rotating-vane vorticity meter was invented by Russian hydraulic engineer A.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In 1913 he proposed a cork with four blades attached as a device qualitatively showing the magnitude of the vertical projection of the vorticity and demonstrated a motion-picture photography of the float's motion on the water surface in a model of a river bend.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Rotating-vane vorticity meters are commonly shown in educational films on continuum mechanics (famous examples include the NCFMF's "Vorticity" and "Fundamental Principles of Flow" by Iowa Institute of Hydraulic Research).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In aerodynamics, the lift distribution over a finite wing may be approximated by assuming that each spanwise segment of the wing has a semi-infinite trailing vortex behind it.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] It is then possible to solve for the strength of the vortices using the criterion that there be no flow induced through the surface of the wing.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] This procedure is called the vortex panel method of computational fluid dynamics.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The strengths of the vortices are then summed to find the total approximate circulation about the wing.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] According to the Kutta–Joukowski theorem, lift per unit of span is the product of circulation, airspeed, and air density.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The **relative vorticity** is the vorticity relative to the Earth induced by the air velocity field.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] This air velocity field is often modeled as a two-dimensional flow parallel to the ground, so that the relative vorticity vector is generally scalar rotation quantity perpendicular to the ground.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] Vorticity is positive when – looking down onto the Earth's surface – the wind turns counterclockwise.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In the northern hemisphere, positive vorticity is called cyclonic rotation, and negative vorticity is anticyclonic rotation; the nomenclature is reversed in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The **absolute vorticity** is computed from the air velocity relative to an inertial frame, and therefore includes a term due to the Earth's rotation, the Coriolis parameter.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The **potential vorticity** is absolute vorticity divided by the vertical spacing between levels of constant (potential) temperature (or entropy).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The absolute vorticity of an air mass will change if the air mass is stretched (or compressed) in the vertical direction, but the potential vorticity is conserved in an adiabatic flow.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] As adiabatic flow predominates in the atmosphere, the potential vorticity is useful as an approximate tracer of air masses in the atmosphere over the timescale of a few days, particularly when viewed on levels of constant entropy.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] The barotropic vorticity equation is the simplest way for forecasting the movement of Rossby waves (that is, the troughs and ridges of 500 hPa geopotential height) over a limited amount of time (a few days).
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In the 1950s, the first successful programs for numerical weather forecasting utilized that equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In modern numerical weather forecasting models and general circulation models (GCMs), vorticity may be one of the predicted variables, in which case the corresponding time-dependent equation is a prognostic equation.
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] where the integral is over a given volume V .
[src:fluid-dynamics-physics/vorticity] In atmospheric science, helicity of the air motion is important in forecasting supercells and the potential for tornadic activity.
